@NODE "intro" "Introduction"

Dear Learner,

Congratulations!  You  have  become the owner of software that, in my most
sincere   conviction,  has  the  potential  to  change  your  life  beyond
recognition.  This  change may be brought forth by a huge increase in your
knowledge  in  whatever  subject  you  choose.  Whoever you are, you would
certainly  welcome  an  improvement in your learning powers. As a student,
businessman,  clerk,  scientist,  teacher, mother, husband or a government
official,  every day, you meet problems that could easily be solved if you
had  some  more knowledge or skills. But, how can you get new knowledge or
skills  when  your  time-table  is  so  tight,  or  perhaps  your learning
ambitions  reach  beyond  your  present  learning  capability?  This  book
presents a simple and sure way to increase your learning powers manifold!

If  you  want  to  learn fast and remember what you have learned, you must
make repetitions of knowledge. It has been proved by scientists working in
the  field  of  psychophysiology  that  everything  that  we learn, unless
repeated  in  any  form,  will  sooner  or later be forgotten. There is no
natural  way  to  avoid  repetitions.  I  do not believe that it is a near
future  nor  is  it  a  very  attractive  prospect  to  learn  by means of
electrodes  implanted  in  selected  brain  structures,  or  by  means  of
chemicals  affecting  the  memory  formation process. At present, the only
effective methods we have at our disposition are techniques that take into
account  natural qualities of human memory.  One of such techniques is the 
@{" SuperMemo " link sm}  method  of timeoptimized  learning.  It makes use of the fact
that  the  key  to  effective learning is in proper timing of repetitions.
What  we want to achieve in optimization of learning is the maximum effect
with  as  few  repetitions as possible. The SuperMemo method, which is the
is  based  on  finding  the  optimum  @{" spacing of repetitions " link  spacerep},  and  thus
reducing learning time to the absolute minimum.

SuperMemo  allows  you  to  make  the greatest possible use of your brain,
regardless   of  your  age,  memory  characteristics,  intelligence,  sex,
previous training, learned subject, weather, bad luck, etc.

From  this  book  you will learn that you can master the principles of the
SuperMemo  method  within  an  hour, even if you are not computer educated
person.  So  why  not to start now? I greatly hope that this will mark the
beginning of your life-long adventure with SuperMemo.

The  primary motivation which prompted me to become deeply involved in the
development  and promotion of our speed-learning software was to see a new
world; a world in which education is a pleasure and provides a solid basis
for  a  brighter  future for all of us. Please accept my whole-hearted and
most sincere welcome to the world of SuperMemo.

Piotr Woúniak
@ENDNODE

@NODE genpri "General principles of SuperMemo"

Before you proceed with installation of software, please have a short look
at the underlying principles of SuperMemo.

Every  learner  knows  from  his  own  experience  that,  after  a dose of
learning,  forgetting  can ruin even the most meticulously woven structure
of  the  learned  knowledge.  The  obvious  remedy  against  forgetting is
repetition.  However,  repetition  is time consuming, and not everybody is
given  a  chance  to  use it in a sensible way. In our times of increasing
pressure  to  learn  more  and faster, most of the students on this planet
waste  a  great  deal  of their life for learning things they are bound to
forget.  Ask  a  recent  graduate  about  the  proportion  of  the learned
knowledge that he or she has retained in his or her brain after a 4-6 year
course  of studies. If the number produced is greater than 5%, it may only
be attributed to the student's poor understanding of the devastating power
of  forgetting. Indeed, forgetting can ruin lives and careers, it inhibits
progress of sciences, medicine, technology and all other branches of human
activity where knowledge plays a part.

There  is,  however, a partial solution to the problem of forgetting:  the 
@{" SuperMemo " link sm} method. The solution is partial, because it does not allow you
to  learn with no effort at all. However, it can be demonstrated in strict
scientific  terms  that SuperMemo helps you increase the speed of learning
manifold.  Indeed,  it  makes  it possible to closely approach the maximum
natural  capability of the human brain to store and retain information. In
the lifetime perspective, SuperMemo allows you to learn 10-50 times faster
than   by   means   of   conventional   methods,  and  to  reach knowledge 
@{" retention " link reten} of 95% or more. How about gaining the level of knowledge of an
experienced professor in just a few years?

SuperMemo  minimizes the effects of forgetting and the overall time needed
for learning.  This is done by  @{" scheduling repetitions " link repsched}  of  knowledge in
strictly determined  @{" intervals " link interval} of time.  The intervals that minimize the
learning time are called  @{" optimal intervals " link optint}.  They are determined on the
base of two contradictory criteria:
    -  Intervals should  be  as  long  as  possible  to obtain the minimum
    frequency of  repetitions,  and  to make the best use of the so-called 
    @{" spacing effect " link spaceeff},  which  says that longer inter-repetition intervals,
    up to a certain limit, produce better memories
    -  Intervals should  be  short  enough to ensure that the knowledge is
    still remembered.

In practice, these two criteria translate into the following one:
Intervals  should  be  as  long  as  it is necessary for a selected, small
fraction  of  knowledge  to  be  forgotten.  This   fraction,  called  the 
@{" forgetting  index " link forgindex}, can vary from 3%, for slower and very exact learning,
to 20% for blitz-learning characterized by lower knowledge retention.

If the forgetting index drops below 3%, the  knowledge  @{" acquisition rate " link  acqrate}
becomes unacceptably low. On the other hand, the acquisition rate peaks at
the forgetting index of about 20%. Above that value both the retention and
acquisition   rate  decrease.  Note,  that  one  can  compare  traditional
learning,   in   which   repetitions  are  arbitrarily  set  in  time,  to
time-optimized learning with the forgetting index above 50%. Such learning
is  not  only  slow,  but  above  all,  the  retention of knowledge may be
unacceptably  low,  and  in consequence, the learner remembers not what he
wants to remember but what is easy to remember.

As optimal  intervals  differ for particular facts or rules that are to be
remembered, SuperMemo  requires  that  the learned knowledge be split into
smallest possible  pieces,  later  called  @{" items " link item}.  If  items  were to be 
repeated collectively,  e.g.,  as  chapters  of  a textbook in traditional
learning, the  overall  optimal intervals would have to be as short as the
optimal intervals  for  the  most difficult subitem in the set. This would
make learning  even  less  effective  than  learning by means of classical
methods. Splitting  knowledge  to  small  pieces  makes  it  possible  for
SuperMemo to  determine  an independent repetition spacing for each of the
items.

Finally,  I  should  not fail to mention an obvious fact that the speed of
learning is not the most important element of education. It is the quality
of  knowledge and its representation that count most. SuperMemo allows you
to  learn  very  fast,  but  it is still your responsibility to select the
learned material and represent it in the most suitable form.

Summary:
~~~~~~~~
1. The key  to  time-optimal  learning  is  in  minimizing  the  number of
repetitions necessary to maintain knowledge in the brain.
2. The  SuperMemo   method  time-optimizes  the  process  of  learning  by
approximating  optimal  intervals  that  should  separate  repetitions  of
knowledge.
3. The knowledge  memorized  by  means  of  SuperMemo  must  be split into
smallest  possible pieces  called items (see sample databases installed on
your hard disk to see how to effectively split knowledge to items).
4. Applying the  SuperMemo method, one must not forget that the quality of
learning  will  depend on selection of the learned material and the way it
is split into items.
@ENDNODE

@NODE HDinstall "Installing SuperMemo 3.0 for Amiga"

To use SuperMemo 3.0 for Amiga you need:
- computer: Amiga,
- memory: at least 1 MB (2 MB recommended),
- operating system: KickStart 2.0 or higher,
Moreover it is recommended to have:
- hard disk: at least 2 MB free,
- CD-ROM if you want to use multimedial databases

If  your  computer  does not meet the above requirements, you will have to
upgrade it first.


Installing SuperMemo 3.0 on the hard disk
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
To install SuperMemo 3.0 on your hard disk, boot the system from your hard
disk, run  HD_Install from the 'SM' directory of the installation disk/CD,
and follow the prompts on the screen.

If  for any reason, your installation does not proceed smoothly, check the
physical  integrity of your installation diskettes. Contact your dealer to
obtain replacement disks, or call/fax Twin Spark Soft.

After  installing  and  rebooting  you can just double-click the SuperMemo
item icon to have SuperMemo appear on the screen.
@ENDNODE


@NODE firststeps "First steps with SuperMemo 3.0 for Amiga"


SUPERMEMO BASICS
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
The main  function  of  SuperMemo  is to supervise the process of learning
pairs of @{" questions " link ques} and  @{" answers " link answer},  which may be combined with graphics,
sound and text. Such pairs are later called @{" items " link item}.  Collections of items 
are stored in computer files and are called @{" databases " link db}.  In order to work 
with  a  SuperMemo  database  you  must  first  open  it. You can do it by
choosing  the  option Open on the Project menu (e.g. by pressing AMIGA+O).
On  the  screen, you shall see the file selection dialog box with the list
of  databases  available  in  the  database  directory,   SuperMemo:DB  by
default.  Double-click  the  database of interest to open it for use. Upon
opening a database, you shall see its learning parameters in the left part
of the main window.

You  can  see  some  of the items of your database using the option Learn.
Choose  Learn  (e.g.  by pressing AMIGA+L) and respond with Yes to 'Do you
want  to  memorize  new  items?  '. Look at the question window. The first
question of the currently used database should appear there. Try to answer
the question,  and  press  Enter  or  click the Answer gadget in the Learn
window to  compare  your   @{" response " link respo}  with  the  correct answer. Now, the
computer  expects  you  to  input  the quality of your answer expressed in
a 0-5 grade point scale. Press any number key in the range from 0 to 5, or
click  one  of  the  grade  buttons located just below question and answer
windows.

The grade point scale is:
5 bright - excellent response; correct answer given without hesitation
4 good - correct response given after some consideration
3 pass - response recalled  with  difficulty,  perhaps  slightly incorrect
(e.g., 5  billion  in  response  to  a  question  on the size of the human
population which was 5.4 billion in 1991)
2 fail - incorrect response which makes you say: I knew it!
1 bad - wrong response  in the situation when the correct one still seemed
somewhat familiar
0 null - complete blackout; you even do not recall ever knowing the answer

You  should  remember  that:  (1)  in  SuperMemo, you are unlikely to need
grades  0  or  1,  and that (2) if you guess the correct answer your grade
must be less than 3.

Your  work  with SuperMemo will, to a large extent, consist in such simple
repetitions  as  described above, i.e. attempts to answer questions stored
in  the  database.  For the best algorithm for learning with SuperMemo see
the  chapter devoted to the options of the Learn option. You can learn the
material  stored  in  commercial or shareware databases, or you can create
your  own  databases  that  will  suit  exactly  your  needs. See the next
paragraph for more details on creating a customized database.

To  quit  repetitions  now,  press  Esc or close Learn window. To save the
currently  open  database  choose  Project:Save  or press AMIGA+S. To exit
SuperMemo press AMIGA+Q or choose Project:Quit  option. Respond with 'Yes'
to 'Do you want to exit SuperMemo? ' if necessary.


YOUR FIRST SUPERMEMO DATABASE
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
In order  to  create  your own  @{" database " link db}  with  items concerning exactly
the sort of knowledge you want to learn follow the steps presented below:
1.Run the SuperMemo program (e.g. by double-clicking its program icon).
2.Choose the option New on the Project menu
3.Input the name and full path of your database. After typing in the name,
press Return or click OK.

This  way,  your  first  database has been initialized, i.e., all its disk
files  have  been  created  and filled up with all necessary data. At this
moment, your database is ready to accept its first item (a question and an
answer).

In order  to  add  new  items to the database, choose the option Database:
Append. The Append window will open. After clicking in the question window
the cursor  will  appear  in  the   @{" question field " link qfield}.  This indicates that
the computer  is  ready  to  accept a new  item.  You can write your first
question now.  Having  finished click the  @{" answer field " link afield}  and type in the 
answer.  Press  Esc  or choose Next button when you have finished. At this
moment,  your  first  item has been stored in your database files. You can
input  more  items  to  have  some learning material for later use. Having
finished  click  the  Append  window and press Esc or just close the Apend
window  to  exit  it.  Make  sure,  however, that you have stored the most
recently  input item in the database. Terminating Append takes you back to
the main window of SuperMemo.


ADDING SOUND AND GRAPHICS TO THE DATABASE
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
Each  item  in  the  SuperMemo  database can be connected with multimedial
information  such  as  graphics  and  sound.  The  files  containing these
information are acceptable in standard Amiga formats - IFF and 8SVX.

In order to join the item with these multimedial data you should:
1. Create a  drawer   for  each  media   (for  example  db_name_sound  and
db_name_graph).
2. Copy all files containing multimedial data to their drawers.
3. Change their  names  -  file's  name should be renamed to a name of the
database with  an  extension consisting of a letter ('a' - for question or
'b' - for answer) and an item number.
4. Set paths to multimedia sources in the Database:Preferences options.

Example:
You  have  a SuperMemo database concerning birds. Its name is 'BIRDS'. You
want  to  add  a sound of a bird which is decribed in item number 125, and
you  want  to add a picture of a bird which occupies unit number 23. To do
it you should:
1. Create a drawer 'Birds'
2. Create a subdirectory 'Sound' in the 'Birds' drawer
3. Create a subdirectory 'Graph' in the 'Birds' drawer
4. Copy the file with sound into the Sound drawer
5. Rename this  file  to  'Birds.a125'  (if  you  want  to  hear it with a
question) or 'Birds.b125' (if you want to hear it with an answer)
6. Copy the file with a bird picture into the Graph drawer
7. Rename this file to 'Birds.a23' or 'Birds.b23'
8. Change paths  to  the multimedia sources to allow SuperMemo finding all
these files.

Searching  through  databases which are sold on the CD you will find, that
sound  and graphics data are stored in another way there. It was a must to
change  the system of storing to make sure, that access to all these files
will be fast and reliable. You will probably never use this system of data
storage so we will not explain the idea of it here. If you are interesting
in it - just contact @{" TWIN SPARK SOFT " link TSS}.


LEARNING WITH SUPERMEMO
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
In the  same  way  as  in  the  case  of  a  ready-made  database, you can 
@{" memorize " link memo} the  recently  input  items  by  choosing  the option Database:
Learn (e.g. by pressing AMIGA+L) and clicking 'Yes' in response to 'Do you
want to memorize new items?' The question of your first item should appear
on the  screen without presenting the answer. You should try to answer the
question before  you  invoke  the  answer   (your   @{" response " link respo}  should  be 
mental or verbal). Having answered, press RETURN key or click the mouse at
the  Answer  button  to  see if your response was correct. Now, you should
estimate  the  quality  of  the response. You can choose any number on the
grade  point  scale  from  zero to five: null (0), bad (1), fail (2), pass
(3),  good  (4), and bright (5). Press the key corresponding to the chosen
grade or click the relevant grade button.

At the  bottom  of the Learn window, you will see a series of numbers that
reflect the   current  status  of  the  @{" repetition optimization process " link optimiz}.
You  do  not have to be concerned about these numbers either now or in the
future.  However,  knowing their meaning will help you understand how your
memory  works  (see  the  next  chapter  for  more  information  about the
optimization  technique used in SuperMemo). All the presented numbers, and
a  lot of calculation that does not meet the eye, are necessary to compute
exactly  when  and which item should be repeated. That's were the power of
SuperMemo is.

After your  first repetition, press Return or choose Next gadget to repeat
the second  item.  The  whole  @{" repetition cycle " link repcycle}   will look analogously.
If you  want to interrupt the repetition cycle press Esc, or choose window
closing gadget.  Your  work  with  SuperMemo  will  primarily  consist  of
inputting new  items  (option Database:Append) and repeating items (option
Database:Learn). You  can  freely  alternate both, but the rule is that on
a given  day  you  should  always  repeat  all  @{" outstanding items " link outitem} before 
you  start  appending  new  items  (you  will  find an outline of the best
algorithm  for working with SuperMemo in the next chapter devoted to using
the  options  on  the  Database:  Learn).  You  can  make  sure  that  all
outstanding  items  have been repeated by finding out that the Outstanding
parameter  in  the  main  window  equals 0+0. To see how SuperMemo spreads
items  for repetition in the nearest days choose Analysis: Burden (e.g. by
pressing AMIGA+B).

Instead  of  creating  your  own  databases, you can install commercial or
shareware SuperMemo databases

If  you  have  a  database  in the text format and you want to use it with
SuperMemo, read chapter about using Arexx.

Finally,  remember  that  before you embark on a full-swing adventure with
SuperMemo,  you should not fail to read the next paragraph which will tell
you  what  to do to make sure that your SuperMemo database files are safe.
Failing  to  learn  the  database  safety  principles may result in losing
results  of a many-month-long effort. It is also recommended that you skim
the  chapter  devoted  to the principles of effective work with SuperMemo.
@ENDNODE



@NODE safety "Database safety principles"

Upon losing  your  @{" database  files " link dbfiles},  you are doomed to forget 30-100% of
your knowledge in the first year depending on how long you have been using
SuperMemo (see the chapter concerning the theoretical aspects of SuperMemo
for an  explanation). To make sure it is not the case, please obey all the
database safety principles listed below.

Remember: one cannot be too careful!


DATABASE SAFETY PRINCIPLES:
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
- Always  leave  SuperMemo  by closing the main window (e.g. with Project:
Quit).  Do  not  keep  an  open database while running other applications,
especially those that could potentially crash the system.
- Be careful  when  running  more  than  one  instance of SuperMemo. On no
condition should  you  open  the  same  database  under  two  instances of
SuperMemo at the same time. In case you attempt to do so, you will receive
the warning: 'This database is already in use (or it has not been saved)'. 
In case of  getting  this  message,  check  the  database  integrity  with
Miscellaneous:Rescue.
- In case  of  abandoning  the  program  in  a prohibited way (e.g., power
failure, system  lock-up etc.), use your backup copy or clean the database
with Miscellaneous:Rescue.
- Do not swap diskettes when a database is open on a floppy disk drive.
- Do  not  modify  database  files  manually or programmatically! Use only
tools supplied with SuperMemo.
- Keep a month and two-month old database backup on diskettes. In case you
intensively expand your database with Append increase the number of backup
generations  to  3  or  more.  Remember  to  make  sure that the backed up
database  has  been  saved,  i.e.  it  is not currently used by any of the
active instances of SuperMemo.
- Keep the AmigaDOS date setting accurate.  In no circumstances should you
change the date setting to differ from the real one!
- Do  not  use  unreliable media  (e.g., old diskettes) or hardware (e.g.,
hard disk used by many users, and probably badly infected with viruses).
- Upon Database  Integrity  Error  message,  backup  your database (do not
override older  backups),   run  Miscellaneous:Rescue.  Note,  that   some
integrity errors may result from the wrong date setting in DOS.
- Recover  from  all  sorts  of  database  damage  only  be means of tools
provided with SuperMemo (e.g. Miscellaneous: Rescue)
- Copy all  databases to RAM: before usage  (Miscellaneous:Parameters/Copy
DB to RAM). It will protect your databases on disks against power failure.

You  are  now ready to start your learning adventure with SuperMemo. Start
your  repetitions  now.  As  your  time  permits,  go  slowly  through the
remaining  chapters of the book to deepen your understanding of SuperMemo.
@ENDNODE



@NODE optimization "Optimization technique used by SuperMemo"

You  do  not  need  to understand exactly how SuperMemo works, and you can
still  successfully  cope  with  your  repetitions.  If  you  do  not like
mathematics,  or  you  are just not interested in SuperMemo internals, you
can  skip this chapter. However, before the screen layout of SuperMemo can
be  considered  in  detail,  a short outline of the optimization technique
used  in  the  learning  process  should  be reviewed in order to lay some
groundwork  for  understanding  statistical  parameters  displayed  during
repetition.

The  algorithm  used by SuperMemo is based on the work of Polish biologist
P.  A.  Woúniak,  who  has developed a mathematical model of memory, which
makes  it possible to compute the optimum  @{" spacing of repetitions " link repspace}  for a
desired  level  of  @{" knowledge retention " link knolret}.  SuperMemo  uses the  Woúniak's 
model,  and  can be programmed to obtain knowledge retention in the 90-99% 
bracket.

Though  the   details  of  the  optimization   technique  are  covered  by
@{" SuperMemo World's " link SMW}  trade  secret,   the  general  outline  of  the  used 
methodology is presented below (patent pending).


OPTIMUM REPETITION SPACING
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
All forms of learning produce molecular changes in neuronal synapses which
form  connections between nerve cells in the nervous system. These changes
are  gradually obliterated in the process of spontaneous forgetting, which
plays   an  important  evolutionary  role  in  optimizing  the  organism's
responses to the outside environment. Forgetting affects all synapses able
to learn,  and  can naturally be prevented only by means of one mechanism, 
@{" repetition " link rep}.  Every  attentive learner knows that forgetting can ruin the
delicate  fabric of knowledge that may take months or years to build. This
is  convincingly  reflected  by  the fact that the Latin saying 'Repetitio
matter studiorum est' is as old as the art of learning.

However,  not everybody realizes the fact that it is not possible to learn
anything once and remember it for ever without repetition!

Even  a  person's  own  name could be forgotten if it were not used, or in
other  words  repeated  as often as it is. The problem with repetitions is
that they consume one of the most valuable assets in the modern lifestyle,
time.  Therefore,  the key to effective learning is to find ways to reduce
the number of otherwise ineluctable repetitions.

SuperMemo  lets  you  learn  at  a  speed  that  is  close  to the maximum
capability  of your brain to form memories. This is done by optimizing the
@  {"  repetition  scheduling " link repsched}, i.e., finding out when and
which  portions of knowledge should be repeated. Considering a given piece
of  knowledge,  there  are  two criteria that can be used to determine the
length of optimal intervals that should separate repetitions:
1.minimization of the number of repetitions,
2.maximization of the overall knowledge retention.

In other words:
1. Intervals between  repetitions  should be as long as possible to reduce
time necessary for repetitions and to produce maximum memory effect.
2. Intervals should  be  short  enough  to  make  sure  that the  repeated
knowledge is not forgotten.

Because of  the  fact  that  forgetting  has a stochastic nature, i.e., it
cannot be  easily  predicted  when  a  given  piece  of  knowledge will be
forgotten, a  statistical  approach  to  the process of learning has to be
applied. By  means  of statistical analysis, we can determine when a given
proportion of  memorized knowledge will be forgotten; hence, the following
definition of  @{" optimal intervals " link optint}:  optimal  intervals are intervals that
result in  a  small,  previously  determined  fraction of knowledge  being
forgotten. This fraction,  called  the  @{" forgetting index " link forgindex},  may be chosen
by the learner, and usually falls into the range from 5 to 15 percent.

By using  optimal intervals in the process of learning, SuperMemo produces
an incredible  increase  in  the  rate  of  knowledge  acquisition without
affecting knowledge  retention. It is not difficult to notice that optimal
intervals will  differ  between different sorts of knowledge and different
learners. The  former  problem is dealt with in SuperMemo by splitting the
learned  knowledge   into  smallest  possible  pieces  called  items.  The
optimization procedure, i.e., computing optimal intervals, is then applied
to  each   of   the   pieces  (items)  separately,   producing   a  unique 
@{" repetition spacing " link repspace} in each of the cases. The principle of applying items
of maximum simplicity is called the @{" minimum information principle " link mininfo}.

The following  reasons  justify  application  of  the  minimum information
principle:
- An  item  composed  of  a  set of subitemms has to be repeated along the
least  @{" sparse  schedule " link spsched}  characteristic  for  the  most difficult of the
subitems.
- Forgetting  a  subitem  included in a composite item requires relearning
all the subitems of the composite item, not just the forgotten subitem.
-  Repetitions  of  simple  items  produce similar or the same stimulatory
effect  in  the  nervous  system in successive repetition, i.e. for simple
neuronal  structures the same neurones are more likely to fire in the same
sequences.  This  makes it possible to apply optimized repetition spacing,
which  is  difficult  or  impossible  to  find  for varying neuronal paths
activated   in   the   course  of  repetition,  and  consequently  varying
stimulation  of  individual  synapses  involved in storing memories. As an
example consider an item which asks for enumerating the elements of a set.
You  can  list  the  elements in any order; therefore, your brain may work
a  different  path  at each repetition. In other words, some synapses will
not  get  their  repetition  at the right time, and the whole structure of
connections will crumble sooner or later.

Note,  that  the minimum information principle concerns the representation
of  knowledge  in SuperMemo databases, not in the learner's memory, where,
for obvious reasons, knowledge should have highly associative structure.

The  problem  of  individual  differences  between  learners  is solved in
SuperMemo  by  application of algorithms that adjust repetition spacing to
memory  characteristics of a given learner. In other words, the procedures
used  by  SuperMemo  can  detect  what  sort  of learning and what sort of
learner  are  subject to optimization. The net result is that a determined
level  of knowledge retention may be maintained in the process of learning
that  approaches  the maximum natural speed with which the learner's brain
can form memories.


OPTIMIZATION ALGORITHM USED BY SUPERMEMO
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
Below is  an  outline  of  how  @{" SuperMemo " link sm}  makes  it  possible  to learn
at  a  speed  reaching  the  limit  of  what  is  possible. If you find it
difficult to understand the details of the algorithm, continue reading the
book.  Understanding the optimization procedure is not necessary to profit
from SuperMemo! Knowing the algorithm, however, may help you interpret the
parameters displayed by SuperMemo during repetitions.

SuperMemo works as follows:
1. The learned  knowledge  is  split  into smallest possible pieces called 
@{" items " link item}.
2. Items are formulated in the question-answer form.
3. Items are  memorized by means of a self-paced drop-out technique, i.e.,
by responding  to  the  asked questions as long as it takes to provide all
correct answer.
4. After memorizing  an  item,  the first repetition is scheduled after an
interval that  is  the  same for all of the items, and which statistically
produces FI  lapses of memory (FI stands for  the  @{" forgetting index " link forgindex}  and 
equals  10%  by  default).  Note,  that  the  first  interval  is randomly
shortened or lengthened for the sake of speeding up the optimization.
5. Initially,  the  first  interval is computed as for an average learner,
but as soon as the recorded value of FI deviates from the requested level,
the  length  of  the  first  interval is modified. Other intervals undergo
similar modifications.
6. After each  repetition,  the  learner  produces  a  number  called  the 
@{" response quality " link respqual}  (grade),  which  determines  the accuracy and easiness
of reproducing the correct answer.
7. On the  base  of the response qualities  (grades), items are classified
into difficulty  categories.  Their  difficulty  is  reestimated  in  each
successive repetition.
8. Different  optimal  intervals  are  applied  to  items   of   different
difficulty.
9. Different intervals  are  applied  to  items  that  have  been repeated
a different number of times.
10.The function  of  optimal  intervals is constantly modified in order to
produce exactly FI  @{" memory lapses " link memlapse}.
11.Each difficulty  category  and  repetition number has its own record of
repetitions used to sketch a separate forgetting curve.
12.Intervals used in learning, including the first interval,  are slightly
@{" dispersed " link dispint} round  the  optimal value in order to increase the accuracy of
forgetting curve  sketching, and consequently, to increase the convergence
rate of the optimization procedure.
@ENDNODE



@NODE descriptSM "Functional description of SuperMemo 3.0 for Amiga"


MAIN WINDOWS OF SUPERMEMO
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
In  the main window  of  SuperMemo,  @{" learning parameters " link lp}  are displayed.
The rest of the screen may be occupied by:
- @{" Question  window " link qfield}, which  displays  the  current  question  (this field
can be used to edit questions).
- @{" Answer window " link afield}, which  displays the current answer (this field is blank 
at times  when  the  learner  is  supposed  to  recall the answer during a
@{" repetition cycle " link repcycle}). 
- Learn window in which you will find:
	+ Gadgets used to perform any action
	+ Grade buttons used to estimate learners knowledge
	+ @{" Item and repetition parameters " link irp}, which  describe  the currently 
          displayed item  and the repetition that has just been made (this 
          field is  filled  out  only immediately after a repetition of an 
          outstanding or newly memorized item; not at final drill).
- other windows  (such  as  G-Question  and G-Answer window which displays
graphics connected with currently displayed item)

Among @{" item  and  repetition  parameters " link irp},  the  following information can
be found:
@{" No            " link irpno}  @{" Repetition   " link irprep}
@{" Grade         " link irpgrade}  @{" Opt Interval " link irpoptint}
@{" Interval      " link irpinterval}  @{" New Interval " link irpnewint}
@{" DATE1 - DATE2 " link irpdates}  @{" New Date     " link irpnewdate}


The @{" learning  parameters " link lp}  could  be  presented  in  two forms: simple or
advanced. Simple method of presentation shows only fundamental information
using bars. You can find there:

@{" <DATABASE NAME> " link lpname}
@{" <CURRENT DATE>  " link lpdate}
@{" <CURRENT TIME>  " link lptime}
@{" Memorized       " link lpmemo}
@{" Outstanding     " link lpout2}
@{" Lapses          " link lplap2}
@{" Retention       " link lpret}
@{" Grade           " link lpgrade}

Switching off  the  'Simple  display' flag in the  Miscallenous:Parameters
option  change  the  default  (simple)  parameter  display  into  advanced
parameters display. The following data can be found there:

@{" <DATABASE NAME> " link lpname}
@{" DATE1 - DATE2   " link lpdates}
@{" Day             " link lpday}
@{" Memorized       " link lpmemo}
@{" Intact          " link lpintact}
@{" Total           " link lptot}
@{" Outstanding     " link lpout}
@{" Burden +/-      " link lpbur+}
@{" Burden          " link lpbur}
@{" Mean time       " link lpmt}
@{" Workload        " link lpwl}
@{" Interval +/-    " link lpint+}
@{" Interval        " link lpint}
@{" Repetition      " link lprep}
@{" Lapses +/-      " link lplap+}
@{" Lapses          " link lplap}
@{" Retention       " link lpret}
@{" Grade           " link lpgrade}
@{" Repetition time " link lpreptime}
@{" Time            " link lptime}


Both  Interval and Burden can be used as a basis for assessing progress in
databases  whose parameter Memorized remains constant. It is worth noting,
however,  that  Interval  is  more  likely  to show global progress in the
database, while Burden and Workload better reflect the amount of work that
has  to  be daily put into repetitions. It may therefore happen that rapid
growth  of  Interval, typical for all users and all databases, will not be
accompanied  by  any visible downward progression of Burden. Burden may be
kept  high  because  of  accumulation of a large number of ill-structured,
intractable items.

Note  that at the beginning of a learning process, the values indicated by
the  statistical  parameters  may  be  highly  inaccurate.  You should not
concern  yourself  about  the  fact.  Continue  working  and  deepen  your
understanding in reference to the possible causes (see also the chapter on
questions  concerning  the  optimization  technique  used  by  SuperMemo).
@ENDNODE



@NODE irpno "Item and repetitions parameters - No"

Displays the number of the currently displayed item.
@ENDNODE

@NODE irpgrade "Item and repetitions parameters - Grade"

Shows the grade scored by the item which repetition has just been made.
@ENDNODE

@NODE irpinterval "Item and repetitions parameters - Interval"

Shows  the  interval between the last and next repetition. Note, that this
field  is  used  to  display the value of the scheduled interval; however,
right after the providing the grade, the scheduled interval is replaced by
the  real interval used between repetitions. In other words, the scheduled
interval could have been shorter if the repetition had been delayed.
@ENDNODE

@NODE irpdates "Item and repetitions parameters - DATE1 - DATE2"

First  date displays the date of the last repetition. Second one shows the
date of the next repetition of the currently displayed item.
@ENDNODE

@NODE irprep "Item and repetitions parameters - Repetition"

The  first number shows the amount of repetition which has been made since
it  has been introduced into the database or since it has last been reset.
The  second  number  shows  how  many  times  currently displayed item has
classified as forgotten. Note, that forgetting an item sets its repetition
counter (first number) back to 1. Therefore, Repetition 3:2,  for example,
indicates  that  the  item has been repeated three times since it has been
forgotten  for the second time. Operation Reset  (Miscellaneus:Reset) sets
the repetition counter to 0: 0. 
@ENDNODE

@NODE irpoptint "Item and repetitions parameters - Opt Interval"

Shows the next optimal interval for the currently displayed item.
@ENDNODE

@NODE irpnewint "Item and repetitions parameters - New Interval"

Shows  the  next  interval  for  the currenly displayed item computed with
applying the @{" dispersal procedure " link dispers}. 

Note that @{" Opt Interval " link irpoptint} and New Interval don't match as a rule.
@ENDNODE

@NODE irpnewdate "Item and repetitions parameters - New Date"

Displays the date of the next repetition.
@ENDNODE



@NODE lpname "Learning parameters - <DATABASE NAME>"

Shows  the  name  of  the  database  in use (it is displayed on the window
panel).
@ENDNODE

@NODE lpdates "Learning parameters - DATE1 - DATE2"

The  database  was  initialized/created  on DATE1, and the current date is
DATE2.
@ENDNODE

@NODE lpday "Learning parameters - Day"

Shows  how  many  days  ago  the  database was initialized. Note, that the
learning  process  might  have  lasted less than shown amount, but no more
than this amount.
@ENDNODE

@NODE lpmemo "Learning parameters - Memorized"

Shows the amount of @{" memorized items " link memoitem} in the database.
@ENDNODE

@NODE lpintact "Learning parameters - Intact"

Shows  the  amount  of  items  in  the  database  that  have  not yet been
memorized.
@ENDNODE

@NODE lptot "Learning parameters - Total"

Total  number of items in the database (Total=Intact+Memorized). Note that
the  last  item  in  the  database  may be listed under a number, which is
greater than Total. This results from the fact that upon deleting an item,
the  database  is  not  renumbered.  Renumbering  can  be  obtain  only by
exporting  database to a text file, and importing it back to the SuperMemo
using Arexx interface.
@ENDNODE

@NODE lpout "Learning parameters - Outstanding"

The  first  number  shows the amount of outstanding items to repeat on the
present  day.  The  second  number  shows  the  amount of the items scored
a  grade below good (4). These items will have to be repeated again in the
@{" final drill " link drill}.  In  other  words  sum  of both numbers shows the number of 
repetitions to be made on the present day.
@ENDNODE

@NODE lpout2 "Learning parameters - Outstanding"

The  first  number  shows the amount of outstanding items to repeat on the
present  day.  The  second  number  shows  the  amount of the items scored
a  grade below good (4). These items will have to be repeated again in the
@{" final drill " link drill}.  In  other  words  sum  of both numbers shows the number of 
repetitions to be made on the present day.

The blue bar represents items for repetition and the black one items which
have to be repeated during final drill.
@ENDNODE



@NODE lpbur+ "Learning parameters - Burden +/-"

Shows  changes  of  the  Burden  parameter  in  the  present  @{" session " link sess} 
(started by opening the database).
@ENDNODE

@NODE lpbur "Learning parameters - Burden"

Shows  the  average  number  of  items  that  are repeated per day in this
database.
@ENDNODE

@NODE lpmt "Learning parameters - Mean time"

Shows the average @{" repetition time " link reptime} per item.
@ENDNODE

@NODE lpwl "Learning parameters - Workload"

Shows  the  average working time with this database. 

Workload = Mean time * Burden (seconds are converted to minutes).
@ENDNODE

@NODE lpint+ "Learning parameters - Interval +/-"

Shows changes of the Interval parameter in the present session.
@ENDNODE

@NODE lpint "Learning parameters - Interval"

Shows the average @{" current interval " link curint} in the database.
@ENDNODE

@NODE lprep "Learning parameters - Repetition"

Number  before colon shows the number of repetition which the average item
in  the  database has been repeated. Second number shows how many times it
has been forgotten.
@ENDNODE

@NODE lplap+ "Learning parameters - Lapses +/-"

Shows changes of the Lapses parameter in the present session.
@ENDNODE

@NODE lplap "Learning parameters - Lapses"

The value in the parethesis shows the requested @{" forgetting index " link forgindex}.  
The  @{" measured forgetting index " link measfindex}  is  shown  as a second  number. In other 
words,  the  second  number  shows  how many items score below pass (3) at
repetitions   (per   cent).  A  large  difference  between  the  requested
forgetting index and the measured forgetting index usually results from:
1. changing  the  value  of the  forgetting index in the Parameters dialog
box,
2. irregular work with SuperMemo,
3. a  very  low  value  of  the requested forgetting index in a relatively
difficult  database  (e.g. the first  @{" optimal interval " link optint}  may appear to be 
less  than  1  day, while SuperMemo uses only integer values for computing
intervals).

Note,  that  with  the  progress of repetitions, the value of the measured
forgetting  index changes at an ever-slower pace. After a longer period of
repetitions,  it will stabilize at some level, and you will hardly be able
to notice any change. 
@ENDNODE

@NODE lplap2 "Learning parameters - Lapses"

The bar shows the  @{" measured forgetting index " link measfindex}.  In other  words, it shows
how  many items score below pass (3) at repetitions (per cent). Note, that
with  the  progress  of  repetitions, the value of the measured forgetting
index   changes   at  an  ever-slower  pace.  After  a  longer  period  of
repetitions,  it will stabilize at some level, and you will hardly be able
to notice any change. 
@ENDNODE

@NODE lpret "Learning parameters - Retention"

Shows  the estimation of the @{" knowledge retention " link knolret}  in the database, i.e.,
how  many  items  the  learner  is likely to remember out of 100 memorized
items randomly selected from the database. 
@ENDNODE

@NODE lpgrade "Learning parameters - Grade"

Shows the  @{" average grade " link agrade}, or  @{" response quality " link respqual},  scored by the learner
in repetitions.  Note, that Grade is a  @{" trailing average " link trailav},  whose changes
are  much  slower for higher values of the Memorized parameter. Therefore,
as  in  the  case  of  Lapses, Grade shows a limited tendency to stabilize
after  memorizing a larger number of items. The honor points corresponding
to  particular  grades  are: 5 - bright, 4 -good, 3 pass, 2 fail, 1 - bad,
and 0 null. 
@ENDNODE

@NODE lpreptime "Learning parameters - Repetition time"

Shows how much time the learner has spent on repetitions.
@ENDNODE

@NODE lptime "Learning parameters - Time"

Shows the real day-time.
@ENDNODE

@NODE lpdate "Learning parameters - Date"

Shows the current date.
@ENDNODE



@NODE menu "Menu tree of SuperMemo 3.0"


PROJECT
~~~~~~~
Project  menu  provides a number of options that affect SuperMemo database
files:
- @{" New                   " link optnew} - creates a new, empty database. 
- @{" Open (AMIGA+O)        " link optopen} - opens a database for use with SuperMemo.
- @{" Save (AMIGA+S)        " link optsave} - closes  the database in use and saves database
                            configuration file.
- @{" Delete                " link optdel} - deletes all files of a SuperMemo database.
- @{" Rename                " link optren} - renames all files of a SuperMemo database.
- @{" Set to default        " link optstd} - sets the database parameters to  their  default
                            form. 
- @{" Quit (AMIGA+Q)        " link optquit} - terminates SuperMemo


DATABASE
~~~~~~~~
Database  menu  provides  options  for  editing,  expanding  and  learning
SuperMemo databases:
- @{" Edit (AMIGA+E)        " link opted} - opens an editing window with the most recently 
                            used item,  and  provides a number of  editing 
                            operations that affect the item,
- @{" Learn (AMIGA+L)       " link optlearn} - opens  Learn  window  and  starts new learning 
                            @{" session " link sess},
- @{" Append (AMIGA+A)      " link optapp} - makes  it  possible  to  add  new items to the 
                            database,
- @{" Search (AMIGA+F)      " link optsearch} - searches for a given string in a database,
- @{" Random Test           " link optrtest} - randomly repeating items in a database.
- @{" Custom ... (AMIGA+C)  " link optcust} - opens a human-supervised learning session  (for
                            all Amiga users who wants to learn on CD32 or CDTV without floppy
                            or hard drive)
- @{" Preferences (AMIGA+P) " link optprefs} - opens  a  database  preferences  window  where 
                            several parameters can be changed.


ANALYSIS
~~~~~~~~
Analysis is a menu that groups options used in the statistical analysis of
the  learning  process.  You can be a successful SuperMemo learner without
ever  using  options of Analysis; however, if you truly want to understand
how SuperMemo works, and how your memory responds to the learning process,
you  will  really  appreciate  the benefits coming from the possibility of
getting the inside view provided by Analysis.

The general application of particular options is:
- @{" Burden (AMIGA+B)      " link optbur} -  to  see  how  many  items  are  scheduled for 
                            repetition on particular days.
- @{" Monthly burden        " link optmbur} -  to  see  how  many  items  are  scheduled for 
                            repetition in particular months and years. 

The  analysis  data  can  be  presented  both  in advanced and simple form
according to Miscellaneous:Parameters/Simple display flag.


MISCELLANEOUS
~~~~~~~~~~~~~
The  Miscellaneous  menu  provides  the following options of the SuperMemo
program:
- @{" Date (AMIGA+D)        " link optdate} - changing the current date
- @{" Parameters (AMIGA+T)  " link optpar} - changing  and storing the set of parameters of
                            the SuperMemo program.
- @{" Cut Drills            " link optcut} - eliminating the final drill queue,
- @{" Rescue                " link optres} - recovering from database damage resulting from
                            the  action  of  viruses,  hardware  failures, 
                            errors on the part of the user, etc,
- @{" Reset                 " link optreset} - converting  of  SuperMemo  database  to intact
                            form,
- @{" Arexx (AMIGA+R)       " link optrexx} - running ARexx scripts,
- Note
@ENDNODE



@NODE optnew "Option Project:New"

This option can be used to create a new, empty database. The newly created
database  will be stored in the database directory specified by the option
Miscellaneous:Parameters/Database Path. 
New  creates  all  files  that  make  up a SuperMemo database, and sets up 
initial values for all @{" learning parameters " link lp}.

To create a new database do the following:
1.Choose Project:New
2.Provide an name for the database.
3.Click OK or press Return.

In case the provided name is not unique, i.e., a database of the same name
already  exists,  SuperMemo  will  ask  you  to  confirm your decision. To
override the old database, choose 'Yes' in a query dialog box.

New  uses optimization matrices from the last open database. This makes it
possible  to  inherit  some  of  the learning parameters at creating a new
database.  If  no database was in use before New, the default matrices are
used.
@ENDNODE

@NODE optopen "Option Project:Open"

This  option  allows  you  to open a database for use. Apart from choosing
Open  on  the  Project menu, it may also be activated by pressing AMIGA+O.
Upon selecting Open, a file selection dialog box appears on the screen.

NOTE THAT TRYING TO OPEN A NON-DATABASE FILE YOU CAN DAMAGE ITS CONTENTS!

After  completing  your  work  with SuperMemo, you should always close the
database  in  use, otherwise its contents may become inconsistent. You can
close the database in one of the following way:
- choosing Project:Save (or pressing AMIGA+S),
- opening  another database (e.g. by pressing AMIGA+O or choosing Project:
Open option)
- quitting  SuperMemo  (e.g. by pressing AMIGA+Q)  or choosing Quit on the
Project menu.

The  database  is  not  automatically  saved  when  you  switch to another
WorkBench  application;  therefore,  it  is  recommended  that you save it
before you start to work with another program.
@ENDNODE

@NODE optsave "Option Project:Save"

By  choosing Save, e.g. by pressing AMIGA+S, you can close the database in
use.  Save also saves the database configuration file (extension CFG) with
parameters  such  as: place and size of windows, font, color, etc. Save is
automatically   performed   on   an   open   database   in  the  following
circumstances:
- opening another database,
- initializing a new database with Project:New
- quitting SuperMemo.
@ENDNODE

@NODE optdel "Option Project:Delete"

This option can be used to delete a database. Delete affects the currently
open database. If no database is open, the Open database common dialog box
will be used to specify the database to delete. All database files will be
deleted, including the documentation, configuration, recovery etc.
@ENDNODE

@NODE optren "Option Project:Rename"

This option can be used to rename a database. Rename affects the currently
open database. If no database is open, the Open database common dialog box
will be used to specify the database to rename. All database files will be
renamed, including the documentation, configuration etc.
@ENDNODE

@NODE optstd "Option Project:Set to default"

This  option  could  be  used  to change all environmental settings of the 
database to default form.  All screen, windows and font parameters will be 
cleared after use of it.

'Set to default'  should be used when screen, windows or font settings are
extremelly inacurate to make an order on the screen.
@ENDNODE


@NODE optquit "Option Project:Quit"

This  option  is  used  to close the currently used database (if any), and
quit  SuperMemo.  Before  SuperMemo terminates, you may be asked to answer
affirmatively  to  the  following prompt 'Do you want to exit SuperMemo? '
(if you have any database open in use).
@ENDNODE


@NODE opted "Option Database:Edit"

Upon  choosing  Edit  (e.g.  by  pressing  AMIGA+E),  SuperMemo  opens  an 
@{" Edit window " link editwdw}  with the most recently accessed item.  This  window belongs
to the group of so-called @{" editing windows " link edwdw}  that make it possible to scan
the  database,  edit  and delete items, etc. Other editing windows include
Search, Learn, and Random test windows.

In @{" editing windows " link edwdw} the following gadget options are available:
- Write - saving  all changes made in the question or answer window to the
database
- Delete - deleting the item from the database,
- Select - choosing another question-answer pair to be displayed; the item
number is used to select the new item,
- Print - placing  the  text  of  the current item in a printer or printer
file (extension .prn),
- Reset - resetting  the  currently displayed item, i.e.  removing it from
the  learning  process and placing it at the end of the intact queue which
stores the sequence of items pending memorization.  All reset items can be
rememorized  by  means  of  Memorize option, or by means of Database:Learn
option.   You  can  use  Reset  to  move memorized items to the end of the
intact queue.  To move items that have not yet been memorized, you can use
Memorize beforehand,
- Memorize - memorizing the  currently  displayed  item, i.e.  removing it
from the @{" intact queue " link intactq} and placing it in the learning process,
- Repeat - repeat  the  sample which is connected with currently displayed
item,
- Replace - swapping the question with the answer,
- Answer - ghosted  in  the  Edit window.  Invokes answer for the question
asked during learning proces.
- Next - displaying item that follows the current item in the database.

The following keys are the most useful in editing windows:
- Arrow keys right/left - to move one item forward or backward,
- Shift+Arrow keys right/left - to  move  a  couple  of  items  forward or
backward,
- Shift+Arrow keys up/down - to move to the first or last item,
- RETURN - to move to the next item,
- Esc - to exit the editing mode, and close the Edit window.

If you start editing the currently displayed item by clicking its question
or answer fields you can use:
- ARROW KEYS - move the cursor (only within the current window),
- BACKSPACE - delete the symbol preceding the cursor,
- DEL - delete the symbol at the cursor position,
- RETURN - cut  the  current  line  and  move to the beginning of the next
line,
- SHIFT CURSOR UP - move to the top line in the current window,
- SHIFT CURSOR DOWN - move to the bottom line in the current page,
- CTRL or SHIFT CURSOR RIGHT - move to the right end of the current line,
- CTRL or SHIFT CURSOR LEFT - move to the left end of the current line,
- SHIFT BACKSPACE - delete  all  text to the left of cursor on the current
line,
- SHIFT DELETE - delete all text to the right of the cursor on the current
line,
- CTRL CURSOR UP - move to the top line of the text,
- CTRL CURSOR DOWN - move to the bottom line of the text,
- ALT CURSOR RIGHT - move to the next word,
- ALT CURSOR LEFT - move to the previous word 
- ALT CURSOR UP - move to first character in window,
- ALT CURSOR DOWN - move to last character in window,
- ALT BACKSPACE - deletes  the  word to the left of the cursor starting at
the current cursor position,
- ALT DEL - deletes  the  word  to the right of the cursor starting at the
current cursor position,
- CTRL X - deletes the whole line that the cursor is on,
- RAMIGA E - erase  all  text  in  a  window  (the  text is saved in  undo
buffer),
- RAMIGA V - paste text from clipboard to current cursor position,
- RAMIGA A - mark all text in a window,
- RAMIGA U - undeletes  (pastes) the last block of text marked, or recover
from RAMIGA E.

When text is highlighted the following keys have functions:
- BACKSPACE - erase marked text (saved in undo buffer),
- DEL - erase marked text (saved in undo buffer),
- RAMIGA X - cut marked text to clipboard (no read-only),
- RAMIGA C - copy marked text to clipboard,
- RAMIGA V - replace  marked  text  with  text from clipboard (save marked
text in undo buffer).
@ENDNODE

@NODE optlearn "Option Database:Learn"

Learn  option  allows you to memorize new items and repeat items that have
already  been memorized. Learn is selected by pressing AMIGA+L in the main
window.  You  can  memorize  new  items on whatever day you choose, and in
quantities  of your choice. However, as soon as an item has been committed
to   your  memory,  SuperMemo  will  determine  the  dates  of  subsequent
repetitions,  and  you  will  have  little  or  no influence on repetition
timing.  Optimally, you should go through the Learn option once every day.
If,  for  any reason, it is not possible to repeat items every day, try to
pass  Learn  as  regularly  as  your  weekly  schedule permits. You should
remember  that  working with SuperMemo once a week will greatly reduce its
effectiveness,  and working once a month can hardly produce results better
than   traditional  forms  of  learning  with  an  unoptimized  repetition
schedule.

Learn proceeds in three stages:
1.  Repeating  items  scheduled  for  the  current  day. 
@{" Outstanding repetition " link outrep}  or  Repetition  appears  in the title bar of the
Learn window.
2.  Memorizing  new  items.  Memorize appears in the title bar. Before you
start this stage you will be asked 'Do you want to memorize new items? '.
3.  Repeating items that caused recall problems in stages 1-2. Final drill
appears in the title bar. This stage starts with the message Final Drill.

Items    repeated   in   the   first   stage   are   determined   by   the 
@{" repetition scheduling " link repsched}  algorithm.  Optimally, all items scheduled on the
current  day  should  be  repeated.  

In  the  second  stage,  items are memorized in the sequence in which they
have been introduced to the database by means of Append. This sequence can
be  modified  by  means of  Reset and  Memorize  (options available in all 
@{" editing  windows " link edwdw}).  Reset used after  Memorize will move the item to the
end  of  the sequence of items pending memorization. You can freely choose
the  number  of new items you want to memorize on a given day depending on
availability of time, tiredness, etc. You can skip memorizing new items in
case there are no more new items in the database, or if you do not wish to
increase the repetition burden.

In  the third stage of Learn, you will repeat items that scored below four
in  the  @{" response quality " link respqual}  assessment  in the first and second stages of
Learn.  If  you have a great number of outstanding items, e.g., because of
vacation,   illness,  etc.,  you  can  resign  from  the  third  stage  of
repetitions.  To  do  this, you should choose the Cut drills option on the
Database menu.

Each  repetition  in each of the three stages proceeds along the following
steps, called the @{" repetition cycle " link repcycle}:
1. The  question of the repeated item is displayed, and you should provide
a  verbal  response,  or you should answer the question in your mind. Upon
producing the response, choose Answer gadget, or just press Return.
2. The answer of the repeated item is displayed, and you should compare it
with the response you provided in Step 1.
3. The  grade,  or  response  quality,  should  now  be  specified to tell
SuperMemo  how  difficult  it  was  to  answer  the question. To input the
quality  press  a relevant grade key or click one of the six grade buttons
under  the  answer  field.  In  case  of hitting the Return key once more,
a  Response  Grade  dialog  box  will  appear  prompting  you to input the
numerical value of the grade, which may then be fractional.

Click  the  Next  gadget  on  the Learn window or press Return to continue
repetitions, or select any of the options of the editing mode (e.g., Edit,
Delete, Reset, Print, etc.).

The response quality grade scale is as follows:
5 - Bright. Excellent response, correct answer given without hesitation.
4 - Good. Correct answer given after some consideration.
3 - Pass.  Answer  recalled  with  difficulty,  perhaps slightly incorrect
(e.g.,  5  billion  in  response  to  a  question on the size of the human
population which was 5.4 billion in 1991).
2 - Fail. Wrong answer that makes you say: I knew it!
1 - Bad. Wrong answer in case when the correct one seems to be familiar.
0 - Null.  Complete  blackout;  you  even  do  not recall ever knowing the
answer.

In  case  you  have  memorized  an  item  that seems less important or too
difficult,  and you think that you would rather wish to memorize it later,
reset  it  (in  the Learn window click Reset gadget). Resetting will place
the  item  at  the end of the list of items waiting for memorization (this
list is called the  @{" intact queue " link intactq}).  Note, that Reset will have no effect
on  @{" intact items " link intactitem}; therefore, if you want to move intact items to the end
of the intact queue, click Memorize before you issue Reset.

If  you  want  to put an important item to the learning process before its
turn  comes  in the sequence determined by Append, you can choose Memorize
gadget in any of the @{" editing windows " link edwdw}.

Here  is  the  best  algorithm  for  using SuperMemo tried successfully by
thousands of users in several dozen countries in the world:
1. Choose  the  daily working time from 5 to 45 minutes. Unless you are an
experienced  SuperMemo user, do not choose the working time longer than 45
minutes!
2. In  the course of your ordinary daily activities collect items that you
want  to  remember  (facts,  figures,  rules,  vocabulary,  names, phones,
graphs,  sounds,  symbols,  etc.).  If  you have directed the installation
program  to  install  sample  databases  on  your hard disk, inspect these
databases to see how to formulate new items
3. Run SuperMemo (possibly one day after you last passed Steps 3 thru 9).
4. While  the  first  number of the Outstanding parameter in your database
is different from zero, repeat outstanding items (use Learn option).
5. If  you  have got some time left for work with SuperMemo, and if Intact
in  your  database  (s)  is  different from zero, memorize new items until
Intact  equals  zero or until your time is out (whichever comes first). If
the  time  passes out before Intact equals zero, quit memorizing new items
by closing Learn window or pressing Esc.
6. Repeat  all  items  scheduled for the final drill. Remember that at the
end of the session you must have Outstanding equal 0+0.
7. If  you  have got some time left for work with SuperMemo, add new items
collected  in  Step 2 (use Append option). If your time is limited, select
only  the  most important items. Keep unused items for later use. Continue
appending new items until your time is out.
8. If  you have a great deal of energy, and you want to work overtime, you
can append more items. But remember: Do not memorize new items after time!
This could increase your burden beyond the daily allotment. Remember also:
Do  not  repeat  items  using  Random  test! This would interfere with the
learning process!
9.Quit SuperMemo, and go to Step 2.

If  it  ever  happens  that  you  are  tempted  to  give  dummy  grades to
provisionally unload the backlog of outstanding repetitions, remember that
dummy  grades may result in irreversible damage to the learning process by
distorting   optimization   matrices.   Mercy   should  be  used  in  such
circumstances,  and  only  as a last recourse. Regular repetitions are the
best cure for the accumulating number of items.

If  repetitions  get  particularly tough, consider increasing the value of
the forgetting index (see Miscellaneous:Parameters/Lapses).

In  case  you  do  not know how to ergonomically use keyboard or/and mouse
during  long-lasting  repetitions,  please  consider  the  fact that whole
learning process can be controled either by keyboard or mouse.
@ENDNODE

@NODE optapp "Option Database:Append"

This  option  allows you to add new items to the  @{" database " link db}.  You can add
a  lot  of new items without ever memorizing them. However, if you wish to
remember  them,  you  have  to commit them to memory by means of Database:
Learn,  and repeat them regularly. You can freely alternate the process of
appending items to your database and learning.

You  can  add a new item to the database by choosing Database: Append, and
proceeding along the following steps:
1. Click the @{" question " link ques} window to start editing the question
2. Input the @{" question " link ques} (use editor commands).
3. Click the answer field to start editing the @{" answer " link answer}.
4. Input the answer.
5. Choose  Next  gadget to input more items, or choose Next or Save gadget
and close the Append window to quit appending new items.

While  inputting  items,  you  can  use  all  options  of  the item editor
described in the section concerning the option Database:Edit.

The following options are available on the Append window menu:
- Next - adding  the  currently  edited item to the database and moving to
editing a new item.  Next is equivalent to Put followed by Cancel
- Put - adding  a  copy of the currently edited item to the databases with
the possibility of editing a new, similarly worded item
- @{"Question" link ques} - editing the question window
- @{"Answer" link answer} - editing the answer window
- Cancel - clearing the edited item

You  can  use the same editing commands as in the Edit window (compare the
previous paragraph).
@ENDNODE

@NODE optsearch "Option Database:Search"

This  option  allows you to search the database for items whose wording is
partially  known.  This  is  possible  by specifying any substring that is
contained  in  the item. For example, if you want to search for items that
concern  viral aspects of AIDS you could choose to search for strings like
HIV,  vir,  virus,  AIDS,  etc.  In  order to search for items by means of
Search do the following:
1. Choose Search option from the Database menu
2. Input the string to search for
3. Press Return or click OK.

Note,  that  Next in the search window resumes searching for the next item
containing the defined string.
@ENDNODE

@NODE optrtest "Option Database:Random Test"

Random  test  randomly select items from the database and presents them by
displaying the question and, after pressing a key, the answer. You can use
Random test for:
- testing your students or colleagues in the field,
- checking  the  percentage  of  items  you  remember (you can compare the
result with the Retention parameter displayed in the main window),
- calculating  the  distribution  of  questions  pertaining  to particular
topics,  or  the  distribution  of various item parameters like repetition
number, number of memory lapses, etc.

You  should  not use Random test to repeat memorized items. This procedure
will only introduce unnecessary noise in the optimization process!
@ENDNODE

@NODE optcust "Option Database:Custom"

As  you  know,  SuperMemo keeps all learning process data and uses them to
estimate  the  next  repetition interval.  This feature is based on saving
all  data  to  a  (hard) disk - and that's why users of Amiga CD32 have to
keep all records themselves.

The  Custom  option  allows  you  to  run  SuperMemo  learning  process in
simplified  form.   Data  about  what  you have learned are stored not for
single item but for sets of items.  In the students hands is to write down
when the next repetition should be done.

This option opens a window in which several parameters could be changed:
- Number  of pages - defines  how many sets of items you wish to learn (in
other words to how many sets do you wish to split hole database)
- Items in page - defines  how  many  items  will make a single page (this
parameters have to be bigger or equal to 10 and less or equal to 40)
- Page to learn - defines which page do you want to learn.

The custom learning process should be done as follows:
1. Define  first  or  second  parameter  (they  are dependend one from the
another)  -  it  is  very  important  not  to  change  them  (use the same
parameters during each learning session)
2. Type-in the third parameter - if  you  start the learning process enter
'1' to learn the first page
3. After learning selected page a CUSTOM INFO window will be opened.   You
have  to  type-in  the  'Last  interval'  parameter which during the first
learning  session is '0'.  If you made a repetition type-in the real 'Last
interval' parameter which you wrote down during the last session.
4. Write  down  the  'New  interval'  parameter  and  the date of the next
repetition  computed  by  SuperMemo.   We  suggest  you  to  write it in
following form of data-sheet:

-----
|   | <- last memorized page
|   |
-----

-------------------------------------------------------------------------
|          Page           | Next repetition date |     Last interval    |
|------------------------------------------------------------------------
|                         |                      |                      |
|                         |                      |                      |

After  learning  session  write down the number of the last memorized page
(in  this  example '1'), in the 'Page' column write down '1', in the 'Next
repetition  date' - the date of next repetition written in the CUSTOM INFO
window and in the 'Last interval' column - '1'.  Use a pencil to make sure
that  you  will  be  able to erase all these data during the next learning
session.
5. Before  each  learning  session  you  have  to  check  if  in the 'Next
repetition date' column you are able to find past or today's dates.  If so
you MUST make a repetition of this page during this learning session.
6. You  can memorize new pages whenever you want.  We suggest to learn new
page  when  you  don't  have a repetition scheduled on this day.  To do it
choose  'Custom' option and type-in the 'Page to learn' parameter which is
one  bigger  than the 'last memorized page' written-down by you.  Remember
to increase the 'last memorized page' on data-sheet.

If  you  feel  that you have problems with memorizing items you can try to
decrease the 'Items in page' parameter.  Then you must start your learning
process all over again.
@ENDNODE

@NODE optprefs "Option Database:Preferences"

In  the  database preferences window you can change several settings which
are connected with database. 

The following sections and options could be find there:
- @{" 'GRAPHICS' section " link prefgraf} - where   all   parameters  connected  with  screen
settings and graphics presentation can be changed,
- @{" 'SAMPLE' section " link prefsamp} - where samples could be switched on/off,
- 'EDITOR' section - where settings of the question and answer windows can
be changed,
- @{" 'SPELL TEST' section " link prefspell} - where spell-checker is controlled.
- @{" 'GENERATOR' section " link prefsay} - where Say Speech Generator is controlled.
- 'CD-ROM  style' flag -  switching  on/off  the  special  system  of data
storage which is used with CD-based databases. 
- 'Link  across' flag - switching  on/off the linking mode which allows to
connect more than item in a database with the same graphics or sample.
- 'Pictures' path - changing  the  drawer  where  pictures  connected with
database are to be found.
- 'Sounds' path - changing  the  drawer   where   samples  connected  with
database are to be found.

SuperMemo  will  be  switched  to  default  graphics  mode by clicking the
'GRAPH.  DEFAULT' button.  Clicking 'OK' button will close the preferences
window and accept all changes.  Clicking 'CANCEL' gadget will close window
and discard all changes.

Parameters associated with a given database are kept in the database files
rather  than  in  SuperMemo.par.  The database configuration file with the
extension CFG is human-readable and may be edited manually (make sure that
you  align  all  variables  to  the same column as originally found in the
file).  It  contains parameters such as placement and size of windows used
by  the  database,  font,  colors,  etc.  The  database  configuration  is
autosaved  at  closing  the  database.  To  restore  the  default database
configuration delete the CFG file.
@ENDNODE



@NODE prefgraf "Database preferences - Graphics"

In this part of the database preferences window you can:
- switch the graphics presentation mode on/off ('Show pictures' flag),
- change SuperMemo screen colors ('Colors...'),
- change screen mode ('Screen Mode...'),
- change SuperMemo screen fonts ('Screen Fonts...'),

All  changes are made using common dialog boxes.  Default settings will be
changed by clicking the 'GRAPH. DEFAULT' button.

All  these options are connected with the currently opened database.  They
will  be  automatically set when the database is opened, and automatically
saved when the database is closed.
@ENDNODE

@NODE prefsamp "Database preferences - Samples"

In this part of the database preferences window you can:
- switch the samples playing mode on/off ('Play sound' flag),

This  option  is connected with the currently opened database.  It will be
automatically  set  when  the  database is opened, and automatically saved
when the database is closed.
@ENDNODE

@NODE prefspell "Database preferences - Spell Test"

In this part of the database preferences window you can:
- switch the spell pad mode on/off ('Spell Pad' flag),
- choose  in  which  part  of  an  item  a  pattern should be searched for
('Question' and 'Answer' cycle gadget)
- specify  the  pattern  which will indicate that in the currently learned
item the spelling of an answer should be checked

During  the  learning  session all items in which selected pattern is find
will  be  learned  by  entering their correct answer into a string gadget.
The  text  typed-in  by  the learner will be than transfered to the answer
window to allow comparison.

This  mechanism  allow not only to learn by heart but to learn spelling of
the words as well.

This  option  is connected with the currently opened database.  It will be
automatically  set  when  the  database is opened, and automatically saved
when the database is closed.
@ENDNODE


@NODE prefsay "Database preferences - Generator"

In this part of the database preferences window you can:
- switch  the  generator  speech  on/off  both  for  question  and  answer
('Question' and 'Answer' flag),
- change   all   system  settings  connected  with  Say  Speech  Generator
('Parameters').

These  two options are connected with the currently opened database.  They
will  be  automatically set when the database is opened, and automatically
saved when the database is closed.
@ENDNODE


@NODE optbur "Option Analysis:Burden"

This  option,  activated by AMIGA+B, can be used to see how many items are
scheduled for particular days.

In  the  three  displayed  columns,  the  following entries can be seen in
particular rows:
- Day - Number  of  the  day in the process (number one corresponds to the
day of the initialization of the database by means of Project: New).
- Date - Date  corresponding  with  any  given  day. Its display format is
determined by the Date format button of the Parameters dialog window.
- Items - Number of items scheduled for the given day.

The  Burden screen may be scrolled back and forth by using Next Page, Last
Page, Next Year, Last Year gadgets.

While    the    'Simple    display'    flag    is    activated    in   the
Miscellaneous:Parameters the burden data will be shown in a graph.
@ENDNODE

@NODE optmbur "Option Analysis:Monthly Burden"

This option displays the number of items that are scheduled for repetition
in  particular  months  and  years.  The present, and the three successive
years are displayed in the monthly burden window To see the monthly burden
more than 3 years ahead press Next Page or Next Year gadget.

While    the    'Simple    display'    flag    is    activated    in   the
Miscellaneous:Parameters the monthly burden data will be shown in a graph.
@ENDNODE


@NODE optdate "Option Miscellaneous:Date"

This  option  on  the  Miscellaneous  menu can also be invoked by pressing
AMIGA+D  and  allows  you to change the date setting kept in the operating
system.  To  avoid  working with a wrong date setting, SuperMemo will warn
you if:
- the date is earlier than the last day on which repetitions were made,
- the date is greater than 30 days since last repetitions were made.

In both cases you will be asked to use the date option. In the latter case
you can confirm your wish to use the database by pressing Return.

In  no  circumstances  should you keep the date setting different from the
real  one!  Do  not  set  the date to the earlier one even if you pass the
midnight  while  working on your repetitions. Do not change the date after
a break in learning!
@ENDNODE

@NODE optcut "Option Miscellaneous:Cut Drills"

This option can be used to eliminate the final drill queue. All items that
score  below  four  in a given session are scheduled for repetition on the
same  day.  In case a great number of @{" outstanding items " link outitem}  accumulate, and
there  is  a  risk of missing a day of repetitions, the final drill may be
skipped  by  choosing  Cut  drills.  Cut drills works by deleting the file
<database name>. REP, which stores the record of items scheduled for final
drill. 
@ENDNODE

@NODE optpar "Option Miscellaneous:Parameters"

The Parameters dialog is displayed by AMIGA+P.

The following parameters can be modified with the Parameters dialog box:
- Copy database to RAM:   - the database will be  copied  to  RAM:  before
                            opening and copied back to (hard)  disc  after 
                            closing it.  We  suggest  to  set this flag in
                            order  to  prevent  a  database  from a system 
                            failure.
- Simple display          - all learning parameters will be  presented  in 
                            simplified form
- @{" Date format           " link parwdwdate} - date format UK: DD.MM.YY or US: MM.DD.YY.
- @{" Lapses                " link parwdwlapses} - the  default   @{" requested  forgetting  index " link reqfindex}, 
                            i.e.,  proportion of items that are allowed to 
                            be forgotten  at  repetitions  (this value may 
                            vary from 3 to 20%).  This  parameter  is  set 
                            individually for each of the databases, and is
                            read at  Open;  therefore,  Lapses  should  be 
                            changed  after  the  database has already been 
                            opened for use.
- @{" Fonts                 " link parwdwfont} - defines default program font.
- Database path           - defines  the path at which databases are kept. 
                            This path will be used by default when you use
                            options  on  the  Project  menu  such as Open, 
                            Save, New, etc.

The  Parameters window allows you to Save parameters to the disk, use them
or  to  restore  previous  parameters  of the program. If you want to make
parameter  settings  permanent,  choose  Save  gadget. This command button
allows  you to store the parameter set on the disk. Parameters are written
to  the SuperMemo volume (or assigned draver). If SuperMemo finds out that
in  the  parameters  directory, the SuperMemo.par file already exists, you
will be prompted to confirm your decision to overwrite it.

Parameters  related  to  the  learning  process are kept in the compressed
database  information  file  with  the  extension  INF.  These include the
parameters  such  as Total, Memorized, Burden, Interval, Factors, etc. The
INF file cannot be modified manually.
@ENDNODE


@NODE parwdwlapses "Parameter Miscellaneous:Parameters:Lapses"

The  Lapses  parameter  allows  you  to specify the requested value of the
forgetting  index,  i.e.,  the  proportion  of  items  that  are not to be
remembered  at  repetitions.  The  permitted range of Lapses is from 3% to
20%.  For Lapses equal to 3%, the learning process will proceed 5-10 times
slower  than  for  Lapses  equal  to  20%  (especially in initial months).
However, the  @{" knowledge retention " link knolret}  will  be  as  high as 99%! For Lapses
equal  to  20%,  learning  may  be quite fast, but retention may even drop
below   90%.  High  values  of  Lapses  should  not  be  used  for  highly
interdependent  knowledge  structures. Low retention can render some items
extremely  elusive,  if  not  completely  intractable.  Such items must be
deleted, or the learning process will grind to a halt (no visible decrease
in the Burden parameter over a longer period of time, even if the Interval
value increases substantially). The recommended value of Lapses is 8-15%.

Note!!!   The  older  the  database,  the   longer   it   takes   for  the 
@{" measured forgetting index" link measfindex}  to  approach  the newly specified value of the
requested  forgetting  index. This is because a large number of items have
already  been  scheduled  in  intervals determined by the old value of the
forgetting index.
@ENDNODE


@NODE parwdwdate "Parameter Miscellaneous:Parameters:Date format"

The  Date  format option of the Parameters window allows you to change the
format  in  which  dates are displayed or input from the keyboard. The two
formats are:
- days - months - years (UK)
- months - days - years (US)
@ENDNODE

@NODE parwdwfont "Parameter Miscellaneous:Parameters:Fonts"

The  Fonts  gadget allow you to specify which font you wish to have on the
SuperMemo sceen. Clicking Select gadget corresponding to the font settings
a  common  font  selection  dialog  box will appear on the screen. You can
choose  the  typeface and size of fonts. The selected font will be used in
all  SuperMemo  windows (except Question and Answer window). If no font is
selected the default system font installed in WorkBench will be used.
@ENDNODE




@NODE optres "Option Miscellaneous:Rescue"

Rescue  is  used to recover from database damage resulting from the action
of viruses, hardware failures, errors on the part of the user, etc. Rescue
should be used each time an integrity error is reported by SuperMemo.

To   recover   from  database  damage  use  the  Rescue  option  from  the
Miscellaneous menu.
Use Rescue in the following circumstances:
- if SuperMemo reports an integrity error in your database,
- if  SuperMemo  reports  that you have failed to close the database after
a learning session,
- if  your computer has recently been attacked by a virus or exhibited any
kind of software or hardware problems,
- if you have not checked the integrity of your databases for over a year,

To clean a database by means of Rescue do the following:
1. Make a back-up copy of your database,
2. Run Rescue
3. Optionaly  Use the file selection dialog box to choose the database you
want to check.

Do  not  interrupt  the  cleaning  process by pressing Ctrl+AMIGA+AMIGA or
turning  computer  off.  Most of the discovered errors are reported on the
screen.  The report file is also generated automatically and stored in the
working directory (its name is <name>. REC.
@ENDNODE

@NODE optreset "Option Miscellaneous:Reset"

Reset is used to convert SuperMemo databases to intact form. In the intact
form,  databases look in the same was as directly after their development,
before  any  learning process started. For example, Memorized=0, Burden=0,
Workload=0,  etc.  If you have a database, and you want to pass it to your
colleague for use, use Reset.

Reset can be used to reset a database to the intact form. Run Reset in the
following circumstances:
- if you have got a database created by your colleague and you want to use
it by yourself,
- if you want to pass your database to one of your colleagues,
- if  you  neglected  repetitions  for  a  period  long  enough to justify
starting the learning process all over again,
- if  you  want  to  reuse one of the databases that, for some reason, you
earlier decided not to use any more,
- if  due   to   database   damage,   Miscellaneous:Rescue  is  unable  to
satisfactorily put your database in order.

To reset a database by means of Reset do the following:
1. Make a back-up copy of your database,
2. Run Reset
3. Optionally use the file selection dialog box to choose the database you
want to reset.
@ENDNODE

@NODE optrexx "Option Miscellaneous:Arexx"

Allows you to invoke an @{" Arexx " link Arexx} script.
@ENDNODE


@NODE Arexx "ARexx"

Arexx  port  implemented  in  the program can be used to control SuperMemo
editing  functions  from  the  outside  of a program.  It could be used in
order to export or import databases from and to a text files.

Three basic ARexx programs are added to the SuperMemo 3.0. These are:
- Demo.sm - which runs SuperMemo database in the demo mode
- Print_DB.sm - which  exports all items of a database to the AmiTekst Pro
word processor (ATP should be run before)
- Make_DB.sm - which imports the text from the AmiTekst Pro and adds new
items imported from the ATP.

As  you  can see, it is possible to make the database in the text form and
then  import  it  to  the  SuperMemo.  The legal text format which will be
accepted by Make_DB.sm ARexx program is:

Q: Question text (max.250 chars) <Carriage Return>
A: Answer text (max.250 chars) <Carriage Return>
<Carriage Return>
Q: Next question text (max.250 chars) <Carriage Return>
A: Next answer text (max.250 chars) <Carriage Return>
<Carriage Return>

Here  is  a list of ARexx commands provided in SuperMemo which can be used
in ARexx scripts:
- sm_to_edit - which enters from idle to edit mode
- sm_to_learn - which enters from idle to learn mode
- sm_to_add - which enters from idle to append mode
- sm_to_end - which exits from edit, learn and append mode and enters into
idle mode
- sm_next - displays the next item in the edit mode (it returns the number
of displayed item or 'RESULT' while the close window gadget is clicked)
- sm_write - adds  new  item  in  the  append  mode (sm_put_q and sm_put_a
should  be used before) (it returns the number of items in the database or
'RESULT' while the close window gadget is clicked)
- sm_get_q - returns the text from question window
- sm_get_a - returns the text from answer window
- sm_put_q string - (where  string  is an input parameter) adds the string
to the question window
- sm_put_a string - (where  string  is an input parameter) adds the string
to the answer window
- sm_num - returns the number odf items in a database
- sm_set number - (where  number  is  an input parameter) displays an item
which is identified by a given number

ARexx port is provided for advanced Amiga users, and from that reason this
chapter of manual is so short and simple.

Please,  refer  to the ARexx programs added to the SuperMemo to learn more
about usage of it.
@ENDNODE


@NODE trouble "Troubleshooting"

Error  messages  are displayed each time SuperMemo detects any abnormality
in  the  status  of  the  learning  process,  structure  of  the database,
environment conditions or user's actions. The three major classes of error
messages are:

- @{" Warnings " link warn} - inform  the  user  of  the  detected irregularity. They can
usually  be  successfully  responded  to by pressing an appropriate key or
changing a program or system parameter.

- @{" Database integrity error messages " link dberr}  inform  the  user  of the integrity
problems  detected  in  the  database. Very often, integrity errors can be
remedied by using Miscellaneous:Rescue  without any loss of data. However,
if not properly responded to, integrity errors can propagate, or result in
a  fatal  error,  and  consequently  produce  significant  damage  to  the
database.

- @{" Fatal error messages " link fatalerr} - indicate  that  SuperMemo encountered a problem
it  was  not  able  to cope with. Fatal errors usually result from serious
database integrity problems or hardware problems. In such cases, SuperMemo
will attempt to close the currently used database. 
@ENDNODE



@NODE warn "Warnings"

Are  you  sure  the date is correct? - This message appears if the current
system  date  is  substantially later than the earliest day on which there
are  repetitions  scheduled  in  a  database  which is about to be opened.
Either  your  have  not  made  your  repetitions for over 1 month, or your
system  date is wrongly set. Press Enter if you want to continue or change
the system date if it is wrong.

Invalid  date!  Last  repetitions  <date>  -  This  message appears if the
current  system  date  is earlier than the earliest day on which there are
repetitions  scheduled  in  a database which is about to be opened. Either
you  mistakenly  made  your  repetitions scheduled for the future, or your
system  date  is  wrongly  set.  Change  the system date, use your back-up
databases, or wait until the day on which repetitions are scheduled.

Cannot  open  <database  name>  -  This message appears if for any reasons
SuperMemo is unable to open a database. Check the following:
- If  all  the  four   @{" database  files " link dbfiles}   are  present  in  the  database
directory. If not, copy the files from the back-up disk.
- If  the  database  files have correct filename extensions (INF, ITI, ITM
and DAT). If not, rename them.
- If  there is free space on the database disk. If not, delete some files,
or use another disk.
- If  you  still  cannot  open  the database, use Miscellaneous: Rescue to
remedy the problem.

Not  enough  disk space - This message appears when SuperMemo has problems
with writing to the disk. Check the following:
- If the database path is incorrectly specified. 
- If there is enough disk space on the database disk
- If the specified drive is ready for operation.

Disk  error  -  This  message is presented in most cases when SuperMemo is
unable to read or write to files.
@ENDNODE



@NODE dberr "Database integrity errors"

Upon  receiving a database integrity error message, you should immediately
stop  the  learning session, back-up your databases and perform a database
recovery by means of Miscellaneous:Rescue.

The database integrity error messages:
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
This  database  is  already  in use (or it has not been saved) - Displayed
each  time  you  attempt  to open a database that is currently in use with
another  instance  of  SuperMemo.  This  message  may also appear when you
attempt to open a database which has not recently been saved, e.g. because
of power failure. Though you need no more than to choose No in response to
Abort the attempt? query in order to open the unsaved database, you should
run Miscellaneous:Rescue to check the unsaved database for integrity.

Wrong  ITM  record  - Displayed if the pointer to the location of the item
text points beyond the end of the ITM file.

Wrong  ITM  pointer - Displayed if the pointer to the location of the item
text points beyond the end of the item record in the ITM file.

Wrong  assignment  pointer - Displayed if the repetition schedule contains
a pointer to an item which does not exist.

Wrong interval - Displayed if a memorized item uses a zero interval.

Wrong  repetition  date  - Displayed if the last repetition date indicates
that the repetition took place in the future.

Wrong E-factor - Displayed if an E-factor reaches beyond its range.

Wrong U-factor - Displayed if a U-factor reaches beyond its range.

Wrong intact pointer - Displayed if the intact queue contains a pointer to
an item which does not exist.

Wrong  intact  queue  -  Displayed  if  the first item of the intact queue
cannot be located.

Wrong optimal factor - Displayed if an O-factor reaches beyond its range.

Deleted  item  in the schedule - Displayed if a previously deleted item is
discovered among items scheduled for repetition on a particular day.

Removing unscheduled item - Displayed if Delete, Reset or Mercy attempt to
remove from the @{" repetition schedule " link repsched} an item which is not scheduled.

Schedule  error  -  Displayed  if  Mercy discovers discrepancy between the
reported and found number of items scheduled for a given day.

Circular intact queue - Displayed if the intact queue is circular.

Wrong distribution of factors/intervals - Displayed if the number of items
in  a  given  factor/interval  category  exceeds   the   total  number  of 
@{" memorized " link memorized} items.

Wrong  ratio Interval/U-factor - Displayed if the relationship between the
current interval and the U-factor is incorrect.
@ENDNODE



@NODE fatalerr "Fatal error messages"

Upon  receiving  a  fatal  error  message, you should immediately stop the
learning  session,  back-up your databases and perform a database recovery
by  means  of  Rescue option. 

For  interpretation  of particular fatal errors see your WorkBench manual.
Check your system software and hardware to avoid problems in the future.
@ENDNODE


@NODE dbfiles "Database files"

Each  SuperMemo  3.0  @{" database " link db} consists of a collection of at least four
files  with  extensions  INF,  ITM,  ITI  and DAT. These files are created
automatically  at  Project:New,  and are updated each time the database is
being  modified. If one of the mentioned files is unavailable, opening the
database  will  be  impossible; therefore, it is recommended that you make
a  regular  backup  of  all  of  the  database  files. The contents of the
database files is as follows:
<name>.INF - Info about the process. For example: Total, Memorized,Intact,
Burden,  interval  distribution,  forgetting curves, Lapses (requested and
measured),  etc.  This file is stored in a compressed format and cannot be
modified by means other than SuperMemo.
<name>.ITM - Text  of  the  items.  This  file  is human readable, but you
should  never  attempt to edit it. Modifying the ITM file is a sure way to
corrupt your database.
<name>.ITI - Info  about  items,  for example: interval, repetitions, last
repetition  date,  pointer  to  the text of the item in the ITM file, etc.
This file is not human readable.
<name>.DAT - List  of  pointers  to  lists  storing  items  scheduled  for
particular days; not human readable.

Modifying  the  database files listed above in any other way than by means
of  the  SuperMemo  program  or other tools provided by  @{" Twin Spark Soft " link TSS}
may  result in destroying the integrity of the database, and consequently,
in an irreversible loss of data.

Optionally, the following file may accompany a SuperMemo database:
<name>.a<number> - multimedia  source  files  associated  with  particular
items.
<name>.REP - List  of  items  scheduled for the final drill (this file can
always  be  erased  without  losing  the  database  integrity). Cut drills
deletes this file.
<name>.CFG - Human  readable  database  configuration file (desktop, font,
color, etc.).
<name>.DOC - Description of the database provided by its author.
<name>.REC - Most  recent  recovery  report  (generated  by Miscellaneous:
Rescue).
<name>.PRT - Entire database or its part in the text.
@ENDNODE



@NODE effwork "Principles of effective work"

It  is  easy  to  suffer  from  a  delusion that the purchase of SuperMemo
software  opens  a  certain  way  to  success  independent  of  the user's
perseverance and thoughtfulness. In fact, the mere personality of the user
is  likely  to  render  SuperMemo  unusable in quite a large proportion of
potential  learners.  The main problem, as in many other human activities,
is  perseverance.  Only strongly motivated individuals are able to persist
in  repetitions,  which,  if not reasonably managed, may become unbearably
monotonous.  For others, the mental burden and short-term time expenditure
seem  to  overshadow long-term benefits. However, there are yet more snags
awaiting  an  unprepared learner. The most important of them are discussed
in the following paragraphs:

@{" Selection of material                                      " link selofmat}
@{" Regularity                                                 " link regular}
@{" Moderation                                                 " link moderat} 
@{" Simplicity                                                 " link simpl}
@{" Univocality                                                " link univocal}
@{" Concentration                                              " link conc}
@{" Awareness of the mental stages passed by a typical learner " link aware}
@{" Pleasure                                                   " link plea}
@{" Health                                                     " link health}

@{" SuperMemo decalog                                          " link decalog}
@ENDNODE



@NODE selofmat "Selection of material"

As  SuperMemo  makes  learning easy, you may be tempted to learn much more
than  you  really  need. Only in time will you discover the true extent of
knowledge  that  pertains  to  your  interest  and  the fact that although
SuperMemo  is  extremely  effective,  it is not omnipotent and, in limited
time,  allows  you  to  master only a limited amount of knowledge. Working
immoderately,  sooner  or  later, you will be overwhelmed by the amount of
repetitions,   and   will   discover   the   true  capacity  of  SuperMemo
(throughput), which is proportional to the daily allotment of time.

Working  with  SuperMemo  imposes a strict limitation on the amount of new
knowledge  that  can  be  learnt  in  unit time, and requires particularly
accurate  selection  of material. In choosing facts and rules to remember,
you  should  primarily  use the criterion of applicability. A multitude of
items  may  seem  worth  knowing,  but  because of the limited capacity of
memory,  only  a  small  fraction  of them may be mastered, and the choice
should  favor items of the highest applicability in day-to-day situations.
You  will not waste much time if you include items that you would remember
anyway  just  because  of  their  high daily applicability. Therefore, you
better  always  err  on the safe side, and include all important items you
are not sure you would remember.

Concerning  the  selection  of  the  material  to  learn,  another general
principle  is that you should first master the most fundamental aspects of
the  learned  subject  and  get  into  details  at  later  stages of work.
Meticulous  dismembering  of  textbooks  page  by page is bound to produce
excess  of  details  at  the  cost  of  principal  knowledge. An important
psychological  aspect  of  the general-to-specialized approach is that you
can  soon  discover great profits coming from the perfect knowledge of the
most  fundamental  facts  in  your field and become yet more encouraged to
expand  your  database  into more detailed areas. With amazement, you will
notice how new facts and rules slot in in what you have already learned.

Good  foundations  make  it  easier  to  fit  in new knowledge structures,
provide  additional encouragement to work, and free you from the unhealthy
impression that you are acquiring knowledge for the knowledge's sake.
@ENDNODE



@NODE regular "Regularity"

The most frequent reason for unsuccessful application of SuperMemo is lack
of  regularity  on the part of the learner. In fact, irregular repetitions
fall  out  of  the definition of the SuperMemo method. No wonder then that
for those who lack regularity success is not forthcoming. Regular sessions
with  SuperMemo  are among the most demanding factors and require a lot of
will  power  and consequence. Indeed, SuperMemo is not only a good therapy
for poor memory, but it also helps to develop iron will.

The  importance of regularity arises from the fact that SuperMemo computes
optimal  intervals that should separate repetitions, and it does not allow
the  learner to delay or advance repetitions. It should not be interpreted
as  a  flaw  of the method, but as a inherent property of memory which has
fixed  mechanisms regulating storage and erasure of memories. Every day of
delay,  not  only  increases  the  proportion of forgotten items, but also
results  in  an  inevitable  accumulation of work that has to be caught up
with in following days. This imposes additional stress on the learner who,
with  each  day  passing by, is less inclined to return to repetitions. In
SuperMemo,  the best results are obtained when the learner uses the method
every day the same period of time. Working every second day, although less
effective, is much better a solution than working every second week, etc.

Systematic work with SuperMemo is a sine qua non of success, and those who
do  not  intend to work regularly should not hope that SuperMemo will make
up for their laziness. To paraphrase a well-known adage you might remember
that  SuperMemo  is  like  sex:  you cannot leave it to others. Treat your
repetitions like you treat your daily religious or physiological rituals.
@ENDNODE



@NODE moderat "Moderation"

It  is  a frequent case that a fledgling SuperMemo learner, enchanted with
results  obtained  by  a  friend  who  used  the  method,  embarks  on  an
exceedingly  ambitious  program  of  gaining  new  knowledge. The thing he
usually  overestimates  is  his  own  learning  capability  as well as his
perseverance.  SuperMemo  does  not  guarantee  that  a  learner  will  be
successful. It requires some skills and working strategy that develop over
a  longer period of time. The fact that a learner can memorize a myriad of
items in a short time does not necessarily mean that the same learner will
have  enough  perseverance  to  sustain repetitions of the newly memorized
material.  Nor  does  it  indicate  that  the  learned  items are properly
structured  and  will  be maintained in memory as easily as they have been
memorized. Two factors contribute to dangers of immoderation:
1. Learning speed  (@{" knowledge acquisition rate" link  acqrate})  decreases  substantially
during  the  first year of using SuperMemo and the decline is most visible
in the first few weeks.
2.  Learning  new  material  is  much  more a straightforward process than
maintaining  the  acquired  knowledge  in  memory.  Badly structured items
reveal their vicious intractability only after several repetitions.

Before  starting  any  extensive  process of expanding his database, it is
absolutely necessary that the learner examine his ability to:
- formulate  simple,  clear and univocal items (with hardly any exception,
absolute  beginners  are  bound  to  form  a  great deal of ill-structured
items),
- work  continually  for  a  longer  time  with  SuperMemo  (only the most
persistent individuals can sustain memorathons lasting more than 1 hour).

Moderation,  and  cool  judgement  of  one's  needs  and capabilities are,
therefore,  a  very  important prerequisite of a successful application of
SuperMemo.  The recommended time of working with SuperMemo is 5-20 minutes
a  day  for  beginners,  and  no  more  than  1-2 hours a day for advanced
learners.
@ENDNODE



@NODE simpl "Simplicity"

It is a very sorry picture to see an enthusiastic SuperMemo beginner waste
his  time  on learning monster items that not only do not want to stick to
his  or  her  memory, but are also absolutely redundant as far as the true
learner's needs are concerned. Imagine a learner who wants to remember all
European  countries  and  tries  to  cram  a long list of their names. The
typical  situation is that he remembers most of the names on the list, but
usually  fails  to  mention  one  or  two.  The result is that the item is
considered  forgotten again and again, and that the learner cannot observe
any learning progress.  Using  @{" mnemonic techniques " link mnemo},  the  learner  could
learn  to  produce  the  whole  list  in  a  determined order, but this is
unlikely  to  represent knowledge which he really wants to possess. A vast
majority  of educated people is unable to list all the European countries,
unless they use the trick of systematic scanning the European map in their
imagination.  Obviously,  learning the list of names is not enough to know
something  about the geography of Europe, and the scanning trick cannot be
done  if  the  learner  knows  the list and nothing more. A good SuperMemo
learner  will  not attempt storing the whole list in one item. He will use
one  of his tricks for knowledge structuring, and split the list into many
items.  Depending  on  what sort of knowledge might be useful, the learner
might use tricks such as:
- grouping items by geographical locations of particular countries,
- by their affiliation (e.g., EEC, Eastern Europe, Scandinavia, NATO),
- by natural language family, etc.

These tricks will certainly introduce information redundancy, but a clever
learner  will  certainly  use  the  redundancy  to  his additional profit.
Monster items consume much more time and produce much less useful memories
than   the   same   items   split  into  many  subitems.  To  ensure  full
recallability,  a  multifaceted  approach  to  a stored piece of knowledge
should  be  taken, i.e., all possible combinations of questions concerning
a  given  relation  should  be  asked.  For example, if somebody wishes to
remember  that the leading cause of death is heart disease, which accounts
for  almost  40%  of  deaths  in western countries, the following question
might appear insufficient:

- What is the leading cause of death in western countries?

It  does  not  let  you  remember the proportion of deaths caused by heart
disease,  nor  does  it  ensure  that the 40% statistics refers to western
countries. Instead, a multifaceted set of questions could look as follows:

- What is the leading cause of death in western countries?
- In what group of countries is heart disease a leading cause of death?
- What  proportion of deaths in western countries is attributable to heart
disease?
- What disease is responsible for 40% of deaths in western countries?
- Is heart disease a leading cause of death in western countries?

Such  a collection of items, although redundant and consuming a great deal
of  time  necessary  for  its formulation, will be learned faster and will
leave  a  more  stable  traces  in  learner's  memory.  The simplified and
multifaceted  approach  in knowledge structuring is the most powerful tool
in  making  SuperMemo repetitions truly effective in the sense of workload
and quality of memories.
@ENDNODE



@NODE univocal "Univocality"

The  fact  that your items are simple, doesn't yet guarantee that they are
easy to remember. One of the powerful obstacles in creating easy databases
is the problem of  @{" interference " link interfer},  or confusion coming from the fact that
two  different  items might have similar questions or similar answers. For
example, imagine that you want to learn something about SuperMemo, and you
create  a  special  database  devoted  to  that  purpose. Consider the two
following items of your database about SuperMemo:

 1.	Q: What is the name of items which resemble one another?

A: ambiguous items

 2.	Q: How are similar-looking items called?

A: equivocal items

You  need  not  much experience with SuperMemo to predict that the learner
who  wants to master a database containing such two items will continually
confuse  ambiguous  items  with equivocal items until he discovers that he
has  two  items  whose  questions  are  semantically identical but answers
differ.  The simple remedy to the problem is to formulate an item with two
optional answers:

 Q: What is the name of items which are similar to one another?

A: a. ambiguous items OR
   b. equivocal items

In such a case, providing one of the answers is sufficient to classify the
item  as  remembered  (unless  the  user wishes to remember both terms and
replaces OR with AND). The problem of interference is particularly visible
in  attempts  to remember numbers. No simple trick of splitting items into
subitems can suffice here.  The  ages long solution to the problem here is 
@{" mnemonic  techniques " link mnemo}.  One  popular  mnemonic  technique is to represent
numbers  as  pictures  and  attempt  to  remember  scenes  formed by those
pictures  instead  of  remembering numbers. For example, instead of having
the item:

Q: What is the value of the constant Pi?

A: 3.14

the learner might memorize the universal list of 10 pictures corresponding
to 10 digits e.g.:

1 - harpoon (because 1 looks like a harpoon),
2 - coin (because a coin has two sides),
3 - tripod (because a tripod has three legs),
4 - dog (because a dog has four legs), etc.

and formulate the mnemonic item in the following way:

A: What is the value of the constant Pi?

Q: 3.14 because: Pi rhymes with fry and... on a small tripod a big balloon
is  being  fried (balloon represents the decimal point), suddenly somebody
pierces  the  balloon  with  a  harpoon, and from inside the broken sphere
a big dog jumps on the learner.

Although  construction  of  the  pictured  scene may seem awkward and time
consuming,  it  ultimately  yields  items that are much easier to remember
than those composed of dry numbers. The net result is saved time.
@ENDNODE



@NODE conc "Concentration"

In  the  pursuit  of  more  and  more  knowledge,  the learner may develop
a  tendency  to  give  careless  answers and hastily jump from question to
question  in  order  to  reduce  the repetition time. There are no dangers
related  to  fast  repetitions  on condition that the speed is achieved by
simplicity  of items rather than by negligence in providing answers. It is
often  possible  to  automatically answer a question without understanding
its  important implications. Instead of being semantic, i.e., based on the
meaning,  the  repetitions  become  syntactic  or  literal,  based  on the
automatic  rendition  of the item's wording. Not only is the thus acquired
knowledge  of  little  value,  but what is more dangerous, the learner may
become  disillusioned  with  the  SuperMemo  method  because of inadequate
progress  in  the  development of desired skills. To prevent the mentioned
phenomenon,  the  learner  must constantly control the learning process by
asking the following questions:
- Is the given item truly important for the skills I want to develop?
- Does  the  ability  to  answer the question truly ensure that I remember
exactly what I want to remember?
- If  I  have  any  problems  with  remembering  a given item, is it truly
formulated in the simplest and most univocal way?
- If  I  have  problems  with  a  simple  and univocal item, what mnemonic
technique could I apply to eliminate my problem?
- Are the following elements of the learning process suitably chosen?
    + The  extent  of  the  subject  I want to master in the context of my
    learning capability and availability of time.
    + The degree to which I want to get into details of knowledge.
    + The retention level I want to reach.
    + The amount of time a day I can afford to spend on SuperMemo.

All  these  questions  must  recur  again  and again, and the learner must
constantly  maintain the highest level of alertness and concentration. The
degree  of  improvement  obtained  by  mastering  concentration ability is
extraordinarily  high  and  worth  while.  Sloppy work will produce little
results and cause disillusionment.
@ENDNODE



@NODE aware "Awareness of the mental stages passed by a typical learner"

You  may  profit  greatly  if  from  the  very beginning of your work with
SuperMemo  you  realize  the stages passed by a typical learner during the
evolution  of  his  understanding  and  attitude  towards  the method. The
observations  presented  below  were compiled from hundreds of letters and
questionnaires  sent to SuperMemo World, as well as from personal contacts
of the author with dozens of learners at both basic and advanced levels.

90% of learners start their affair with SuperMemo because of good opinions
they heard about the program from their colleagues or from press. In other
words,  the  initial  attitude  is positive and full of expectation. After
studying  the basics of SuperMemo, reactions of learners vary greatly, and
are   highly  correlated  with  the  general  level  of  intelligence  and
education, especially with respect to exact sciences.

A  substantial  group of learners become discouraged because of mechanical
and  repetitive  nature  of SuperMemo workouts. In this group, individuals
with  no  university  education,  or  university  education  in humanities
strongly  prevail.  On  the other end of the spectrum are individuals with
strong  background in mathematics, physics or computing sciences, who seem
to  have  fewer  problems with grasping the basics of SuperMemo, and whose
first  contact  with  the  method  is  likely  to  enhance  their positive
attitude.  From this group, SuperMemo has recruited the greatest number of
enthusiastic supporters.

Only  75%  of individuals continue their repetitions beyond one month! The
drop-outs  provide the following reasons for cessation of repetitions: (1)
they  do  not  believe  in  SuperMemo  (10%,  no  university  education or
education  in  humanities),  (2) they do not believe in their own learning
powers (5%, mostly individuals over 45 years of age, and women - housewife
type),  (3)  they  do  not  have time for repetitions (25%, mostly private
entrepreneurs,  physicians,  lawyers, etc.), and (4) they intend to return
to repetitions in the future (60%, students).

Only  those  learners  who  pass  the first month of repetitions can truly
testify  to the usefulness of the method. Among those the approval rate is
95%! Most of them consider SuperMemo an excellent aid in learning (50%) or
a  useful  product (45%); only 5% of those polled did not have a specified
opinion or rated SuperMemo as nothing special.

SuperMemo World has not received a single questionnaire from a learner who
had  tried  out  SuperMemo  for  at  least  one  month,  and was generally
dissatisfied  with  the method or the program. However, the attrition rate
after  the  first  month  remains  still  high.  Having  passed a month of
repetitions,   almost  all  learners  wish  they  had  used  SuperMemo  on
a  permanent basis, but for hundreds of reasons they cannot cope with busy
repetition  schedules.  The  most widespread attitude is to hope to resume
repetitions  in  some  unspecified  future.  Here,  the  major drawback of
SuperMemo  becomes  visible: it does not produce amazing results for free!
It  does  produce  amazing  results,  but only through hard and systematic
work.   In  busy  times  of  our  dynamically  growing  and  hazard-ridden
civilization,  we  all too often stick to the principle that better an egg
today  than  a  hen tomorrow. 10 minutes spent on a business call, reading
a  scientific  paper,  or writing a report seem to bring immediate result.
The  same  10  minutes spent on reasonable repetitions with SuperMemo, can
save several hours or even days in the lifetime, but the saving is hard to
sense, even for an experienced learner. Moreover, after a longer period of
repetitions,  the learner may easily come to the false conclusion that the
knowledge  has already been mastered, and requires no further repetitions.
Thus  even the most enthusiastic learners often drop weeks of repetitions;
the  more  so,  that  abusing  Mercy  and  Reset  can  easily  produce the
impression  that all is OK with the learning process. For an average user,
breaks in repetitions regularly make up 20% of the learning time.

You  should not forget that you are not the only one who says I will do it
tomorrow,  or  next  week,  or  I  think  I  still  remember it all right.
Forgetting  is  like  radiation: you cannot smell it, you cannot taste it,
and when you finally notice its power, the damage is already irreversible.
@ENDNODE



@NODE plea "Pleasure"

There is a sure way to tell that a given learner will be successful in his
work  with  SuperMemo.  If he finds pleasure in long-lasting sessions with
repetitory  work,  he  is bound to do terrific job. Despite what meets the
eye  at first, SuperMemo repetitions do not have to be monotonous. Here is
a  couple  of  examples of extra activities that accompany repetitions and
provide  a splendid ground to make the work with SuperMemo interesting and
challenging:
- Modification  of items that do not seem to comply with the principles of
simplicity and univocality.
- Removal of items that no longer seem worth remembering.
- Cross-analysis  of  the database, in order to eliminate discrepancies or
redundancy  (e.g.,  by  means  of  Search).  Note  that  not  all sorts of
redundancy  are  undesirable.  For  example,  having the same foreign word
twice  in  a  databases  introduces  unnecessary noise in the optimization
process;  however,  having  the  same  word  in  different  contexts might
increase its semantic associativeness.
- Appending new items.
- Analysis of the repeated items:
    1. What  does  a  given  fact  or rule imply? Does it agree with other
    facts I know?
    2. In  what  situations can I use the knowledge I learn? What will the
    profit or satisfaction be?
    3. In what situation did I find that I should remember the given item?
    Was I really able to make use of knowing it?
- Inspection   of  statistical  data  used  in  monitoring  the  learner's
progress, etc.

If  the  repetition  process  appears  to  be  tedious and monotonous, the
learner  must seriously reconsider all the earlier mentioned prerequisites
of success in work with SuperMemo. Lack of enthusiasm is the first symptom
of  misguided  application of the method. On the other hand, if reasonably
and consequently applied, SuperMemo appears to be extremely addictive, and
you   will   find  it  absolutely  indispensable  for  your  personal  and
professional success.
@ENDNODE



@NODE health "Health"

As  in  most  human  activities,  general  health  helps to achieve better
results  in  the  process  of  learning.  It increasingly becomes a common
knowledge how to keep healthy and fit. It may still, however, be useful to
list  the  most  important  principles  that should be remembered by every
learner:
-  Sufficient  amount  of sleep. It is during sleep that the conversion of
short-term  to long-term memories takes place. Particularly, the REM phase
of  sleep  is valuable, and each all-nighter reduces the proportion of REM
sleep  in  the  next  night. Intense intellectual work may cause increased
demand  for  sleep, and nothing should prevent the learner from satisfying
it.  No  one has ever benefited from trying to save time by sleeping less.
By  trying  to  emulate  Edison, the learner is bound to reduce his or her
performance.  Tiredness caused by lack of sleep is one of the main factors
that  can  ruin  a  SuperMemo  session.  On  the other hand, 40 minutes of
SuperMemo a day are likely to increase your natural demand for sleep by up
to one hour!
-  Physical exercise is absolutely necessary for every successful learner.
Without it, the respiratory and circulatory systems cannot adapt easily to
increased demand for oxygen in intense intellectual work. An unfit learner
tends  to  be drowsy and cannot maintain the sufficient level of alertness
in   long  sessions  with  SuperMemo.  Pains  of  the  back,  eye  strain,
hemorrhoidal   problems,  gastrointestinal  disorders,  repetitive  strain
injury,  and  many  other  ailments  of a hard-working learner are greatly
prevented  by  a  high  level of fitness in physically active individuals.
Sports that result in a long-lasting increase in the heart rate and oxygen
consumption,   e.g.,   jogging,   intense   cycling,  swimming,  etc.  are
particularly recommended.
-  It is a common knowledge that smoking and alcohol are major preventable
causes  of  a great spectrum of disorders that not only interfere with the
process  of  learning,  but are also dangerous for health and, in the long
run, life. Alcoholism is notorious for its toxic effects to the brain, and
is  a  major environmental cause of senile dementia (loss of memory in old
age).  Smoking  is most renowned for its contribution to heart disease and
cancer;  however, even for a learner who is not much concerned with his or
her  own future, it is worth noting that smoking also causes hypertension,
increased  excitability  of  the nervous system, cerebral hypoxia (reduced
oxygenation  of  the  brain)  and  many  other  effects  that  are  highly
undesirable in learning.
-  Adequate  nutrition  is  indispensable  in  successful  learning. It is
difficult  to  specify  particular guidelines except for the fact that the
foods  consumed  should comply with what is generally considered a healthy
diet.  For  example,  everybody  knows  from  one's  own  experience  that
a satisfying lunch makes one more inclined to get down to learning, but on
the  other  hand, research demonstrates that the level of mental alertness
drops  substantially  after  a  meal. It is also known that a low-fat diet
prevents  arteriosclerosis  and  should  be considered desirable. However,
another  research  shows that reduced blood level of lipoproteins (a group
of  fat  components)  has  a  negative  influence  on  the  performance in
intelligence  tests.  An  average,  healthy  diet  should  satisfy all the
nutritional needs of a learner, so that no supplements shall be necessary.
Regular  administration  of  vitamins,  particularly  B  and C, or mineral
preparations, however, might be of preventive value.
- Tea and coffee are used by many people as stimulants, especially in case
of  sleep  deficit.  While having a positive effect on the alertness, high
levels  of  caffeine  and teophylline (active compounds of coffee and tea)
may  cause  restlessness,  problems  with concentration and, worst of all,
sleep   disturbances.   Both   drinks,   as   well   as   all   sorts   of
caffeine-containing colas, should be used with moderation.
-  In  the state of rest, the brain uses only a small proportion of oxygen
that  is  bound  to  hemoglobin in the lungs. However, in cases of intense
intellectual  work,  it  may use up 30 or more percent of total oxygen. As
you  will observe, SuperMemo is a particularly tiring technique, primarily
because  it  forces  your  brain  to work at its top gear (repetitions are
scheduled  on the verge of forgetting). An average, untrained learner will
experience  an  overwhelming  drowsiness  as  soon  as after 20 minutes of
continuous  repetitions.  Most  of  individuals find it impossible to work
with SuperMemo for more that 1 hour, and each minute beyond that limit may
bring  a  genuine mental torture. This entails the great importance of the
availability  of  fresh  air  in  the  room when the learning takes place.
Sufficient amount of sleep, fresh air and enthusiasm for work are the best
allies  of  a learner who wishes to spend long sessions with SuperMemo and
to produce fabulous results.
@ENDNODE



@NODE decalog "SuperMemo decalog"

1. Create  your  databases using only the most applicable knowledge. Don't
get too far into details before forming a general picture of the field you
want to master.

2. Work the same amount of time every day. Don't overwork.

3. Before  embarking  on intense expansion of your database, check if your
ability  to formulate easy-to-remember items is sufficient, and check what
your  mental  powers  are  and  how  much  time  you can afford to sustain
long-lasting repetition process.

4. Make  sure  that your items are as simple as possible and that they ask
about all important aspects of the learned fact or rule.

5. Use mnemonic techniques for the most intractable items.

6. Concentrate  and don't  stop thinking. Repetitions should be conscious,
not automatic.

7. If  you  ever  decide  to  suspend  repetitions  for  a period of time,
remember  that  this  is a sure way to drop out, and never to discover the
true value of SuperMemo.

8. If you do not find working with SuperMemo pleasant, then stop appending
new  items  and pay more attention to cleaning your databases from useless
or ill-structured garbage.

9. Keep fit.  Do not cut down on sleep, exercise regularly and give up all
hazardous habits like smoking or drinking.

10. Read  the above rules from time to time or formulate them as SuperMemo
items that could be placed in one of your databases.
@ENDNODE



@NODE theory "Theoretical aspects of using the SuperMemo method"

This chapter is intended for advanced SuperMemo learners who would like to
know  more  about  how SuperMemo works in a longer perspective, and how to
plan  and  supervise  the learning process in a more conscious way. Deeper
understanding  of  the  SuperMemo  method,  and  some  basic  knowledge of
mathematical  concepts  is  necessary to make this chapter a good reading.
Most of the presented findings were obtained in either of the two ways:
- by collecting data during a real SuperMemo learning process
- by using the mathematical model of memory developed by Piotr Woúniak.

The following facts and rules concerning SuperMemo have been found:

1. The  learning  curve obtained by using the SuperMemo method, except for
the very initial period, is almost linear.

2. In a  long-term process, for the  @{" forgetting index " link forgindex}  equal to 10%, the
average rate of learning for well-structured databases can be approximated
to  200-300 items/year/min, i.e. one minute of learning per day results in
acquisition of 200-300 items per year (note, that the term well-structured
depends on the capability of the learner).

3. The  number  of  items  memorized in consecutive years when working one
minute a day can be approximated with the following equation:

   new_items=aar*(3*e-0.3*year+1)

   where:
   new_items - items  memorized  in  consecutive  years  when  working one 
               minute per day,
   year      - ordinal number of the year,
   aar       - asymptotic  @{" acquisition rate " link acqrate},  i.e.  the minimum learning
               rate reached after many years of repetitions (usually about 
               200 items/year/min).

4. Eliminating  10%  of the most difficult items in a generic database may
produce  an increase in the speed of learning of up to 300%. The lower the
forgetting index, the greater the increase.

5. In  a  long-term process, for the forgetting index equal to 10% and for
a fixed daily working time, the average time spent on memorizing new items
is  only  5% of the total time spent on repetitions (repeating outstanding
items   and  memorizing  new  items).  Note  that  this  value  is  almost
independent of the size of the database.

6. After cessation of repetitions, the forgetting rate is much higher than
the knowledge acquisition rate.

7. For  a  well-structured  database  and  the  forgetting  index  of 10%,
cessation  of  repetitions  after  1 year of learning will produce loss of
about 95% of the learned material in the first year.

8. For  a  well-structured  database  and  the  forgetting  index  of 10%,
cessation  of  repetitions after 5 years will produce loss of about 60% of
the learned material in the first year.

9. For  a  well-structured  database  and  the  forgetting  index  of 10%,
cessation  of repetitions after 20 years will produce loss of about 30% of
the learned material in the first year.

10. The  maximum  lifetime  capacity  of  the  human  brain to acquire new
knowledge  by  means of SuperMemo can be estimated as no more than several
million items.

11. For  a well-structured database and the forgetting index of about 10%,
the  function  of time required daily for repetitions per item can roughly
be approximated using the formula:

   time = 1/500 * year -1.5 +  1/30000

   where:
   time - average daily time spent for repetitions per item in a given 
          year (in minutes),
   year - year of the process.

Because  of the nature of SuperMemo, the time necessary for repetitions of
a  single  item  is  almost  independent  of the total size of the learned
material.  Therefore,  the  above  formula  may be used to approximate the
workload  for  databases  of any size. For example, the total workload for
a  3000  item database in the first year will be 3000/500*1+3000/30000=6.1
(min/day).

12. The  relationship  @{" forgetting index " link forgindex}  vs.  @{" knowledge retention " link knolret}  can 
accurately be expressed using the following formula:

   Retention = 100 - FI/2.2

   where:
   Retention - overall knowledge retention expressed in percent,
   FI        - forgetting  index  expressed  in  percent (forgetting index 
               equals 100% - knowledge retention at repetitions).

13. The  greatest  overall  increase  in  the  @{" optimal interval " link optint}  can  be
observed for the forgetting index of about 20%. The overall increase takes
into  the  consideration  the  fact  that for forgotten items, the optimal
interval  decreases. Therefore, for the forgetting index greater than 20%,
the  positive  effect  of  long  intervals  on memory  resulting  from the
@{" spacing effect " link spaceeff} is offset by the increasing number of forgotten items.

14. The  greatest  overall  knowledge acquisition rate is obtained for the
forgetting  index of about 20-25%. This results from the trade-off between
reducing the repetition workload and increasing the relearning workload as
the forgetting index progresses upward. In other words, high values of the
forgetting  index result in longer intervals, but the gain is offset by an
additional  workload  coming from a greater number of forgotten items that
have to be relearned. Note, that for most of traditional forms of learning
the  forgetting  index  stands  well  above  90%! This means that by using
a  standard  read-and-review  learning  procedure  with no optimization of
repetition  scheduling,  the learning time will be 10 times longer than in
SuperMemo, and the retention will range from 5-20% as compared with 85-99%
in SuperMemo.

15. When  the  forgetting  index  drops  below 5%, the repetition workload
increases  rapidly.  The recommended value of the forgetting index used in
the practice of SuperMemo repetitions is 6-14%.

16. As  compared   with  equally  spaced  repetition  schedules,  for  the
forgetting  index  equal  to  10%,  SuperMemo  produces  an  about 50-fold
increase in the speed of learning.
@ENDNODE



@NODE q&a "Questions asked by users and potential users of SuperMemo"

Here  is a collection of questions often asked by users of SuperMemo. Read
this  chapter  if you cannot find answers to your questions in other parts
of the manual. In case you still have doubts or problems after reading the
list  below,  write to  @{" SuperMemo World " link SMW}  or  @{" Twin Spark Soft "  link  TSS}  (see the
chapter  about  these firms for the best way to contact us). Within bounds
of   possibility,  SuperMemo  World  customer  service  will  answer  your
questions  in  writing,  and,  if  possible,  include  the  answer in this
chapter. The questions are grouped into the following categories:

@{" General knowledge about SuperMemo " link genq&a}
@{" Using SuperMemo                   " link basicq&a}
@{" SuperMemo Toolkit                 " link toolq&a}
@{" Theoretical aspects of SuperMemo  " link theoryq&a}
@ENDNODE



@NODE genq&a "General questions"

Q: Can a computer-illiterate person use SuperMemo?

A: Yes.  The  entire  knowledge needed to start is encompassed in the page
long  Minimum  User's  Guide which is present at the first chapter of this
text.  Five  simple  operations  needed to use SuperMemo can be learned in
less than 10 minutes! No specialized knowledge is required.


Q: If I don't have a computer, can I use SuperMemo?

A: Yes.  A  limited,  paper-and-pencil variant of SuperMemo exists. If you
are interested in it, please contact @{" SuperMemo World " link SMW}.


Q: Can I use SuperMemo in a computer lab?

A: Yes,  on  condition  that  the access to computers in the laboratory is
regular.  Once  you  start  working  with SuperMemo, you must continue the
process  of  repetitions. Otherwise, the acquired knowledge will gradually
be  forgotten  (e.g.  if you stop after having used SuperMemo for 5 years,
you will forget about 60% of the learned material in the first year!)


Q: Do you have SuperMemo for Mac, Amiga, Atari, etc.

A: SuperMemo is available for DOS, Windows, Amiga and Mac. 
To   learn   more   about  the  PC  version  contact:  @{" SuperMemo  World " link SMW},
ul.  R. Maya 1, 61-371 Poznaď, tel/fax (48) 61 764073; fax (48) 61 793435,
e-mail: jam@plpuam11.bitnet, jam@brahms.udel.edu
To  learn  more  about  the  Amiga  version  contact:   @{" Twin Spark Soft " link TSS},
ul.  M.  Samozwaniec  18,  P.  O. BOX 18, 31-711 Kraków 60, Poland,
tel/fax: (48) 12 431537
To  learn more about the Mac version contact: Madland tel. (48) 52 725900,
725916, 717146.


Q: What are the minimum hardware requirements of SuperMemo for Amiga?

A: The requirements are as follows: Kickstart 2.0 or higher, 2MB RAM, Hard
Disk recommended


Q: What are the basic differences between SuperMemo 2.0 and 3.0?

A: SuperMemo 3.0 allows you to associate graphics and sound with SuperMemo
items.  It  support  all  Kickstart 2.0/3.0 benefits such as localization,
on-line  help,  and  various  screen  modes.  It  works with CD-ROM's (new
generation of databases using samples and graphics stored on CD's).


Q: Can  I  write  my  own  SuperMemo  databases  concerning  topics  of my
interest?

A: Yes.


Q: If  I  prepare  a  database  for  SuperMemo, can I sell it to SuperMemo
World?

A: Yes.  Particularly  if  it  is a good database, on a popular topic, and
preferably written in English. Otherwise, your database may be included in
the  @{" Database Bank " link bank},  and  you will be paid royalties from each copy sold
(standardly 10% of the end-user price).


Q: What databases are there in the SuperMemo World's Database Bank?

A: See the DBANK. TXT file for the most recent list of databases available
from the Database Bank.


Q: What is SuperMemo World e-mail?

A: If you have an important problem, you might try one of the following:
- JAM@BRAHMS.UDEL.EDU [English, Polish] (technical problems)
- JAM@PLPUAM11.BITNET [English]  (theoretical  questions  about SuperMemo,
proposed improvements to software, biological aspects of memory)
- SUPRMEMO@PRAIRIENET.ORG [English] (orders and distribution in the US)
- ALM@UX1.CSO.UIUC.EDU [English] (orders and distribution in the US)

All  e-mail  messages are read carefully. Please understand, however, that
we are unable to answer all e-mail inquiries.
@ENDNODE



@NODE basicq&a "Basic questions concerning the use of SuperMemo"

Q: Why does SuperMemo ask only those items which are difficult?

A: Just  because  they are difficult.  You do not want to learn things you
already  know, do you? The purpose of SuperMemo optimization is to compute
the  best  intervals between repetitions. Difficult items must be repeated
more  often;  hence  the  impression  that  only  the  hardest  items  are
considered in the process.


Q: I  found  some  errors  and  misspellings  in  your databases.  How can
I correct them?

A: When  you see the wrong item on the screen you must enter the edit mode
(EDIT  window  will  be  opened),  click  the  mistaken field (question or
answer)  and  edit  the item using arrow keys, Backspace, etc. Remember to
Write all changes made in the item.


Q: The  User's Guide often mentions that the user should periodically back
up his or her databases. What does it mean and how to do it?

A: To  back  up a file means to copy it to an archive diskette in case the
original  file was lost or damaged. You can back up your files by means of
AmigaDOS  commands  such  us,  as  well  as by means of tools such as File
Master, DOpus etc.


Q: How can I increase the frequency of repetitions before an exam?

A: SuperMemo  is  not supposed to be used as a cramming tool. It is rather
designed for those who want to keep knowledge in their memory for a longer
period  of  time (from one year to lifetime). To maximize the frequency of
repetitions  set  Lapses  to 3 (option Miscellaneous:Parameters).  The day
before  the  exam  you  might  try  Random  test,  but this will certainly
introduce a lot of noise into your long-term learning process.


Q: I want to learn Russian. Can SuperMemo provide Cyryllic?

A: Yes.  To  get  Cyryllic  in  your  items do the following:  (1) install
Cyryllic in Fonts draver (choose a commercial or shareware font, or define
the  font  using  any  font editor), and (2) choose Cyryllic font for your
RUSSIAN database (option Miscellaneous:Multimedia).


Q: How can I learn mathematical formulas in SuperMemo?

A: You can choose one of the following:
- use TEX syntax if you know it,
- represent you formulas using graphics,
- define  your  own  font  with mathematical symbols or use a commercially
available font that would satisfy your needs.


Q: When  I  back  up my databases, do I have to back up SuperMemo files as
well?

A: No.


Q: How can a whole family use SuperMemo on one computer?

A: Install one copy of SuperMemo and duplicate these databases that are to
be  used  by  the  members  of  the  family. You can store databases under
different  names  in  the  default database directory (e.g. databases MUM,
DAD,  CATE  in  the  subdirectory DB), or under the same name in different
subdirectories  (e.g.  database  ENGLISH  in subdirectories DM/MUM, DB/DAD
etc.).  The  first  solution is somewhat better, as upon running SuperMemo
you  will  automatically  be positioned in the default database directory,
and  will  have  to specify the database name only at Open. Otherwise, the
full path should be specified or located by browsing the directory tree.


Q: I  would  like  to  keep  the  definition of backgammon in my SuperMemo
database,  but  I cannot cut the Webster wording to suit the 250 character
limit,  and  yet  make  the definition understandable: a board game played
with  dice  and  counters  in which each player tries to move his counters
along  the  board  and at the same time to block or capture his opponent's
counters...

A: If you do not know what backgammon is,  you should not attempt to store
the   rules  of  the  game  in  just  one  definition!   See  the  chapter
@{" principles of effective work " link effwork}  with SuperMemo.  Simplicity  to  get  some
clues on how to formulate items. You might choose one or two features that
define  backgammon unambiguously, and keep the rest of details in separate
items, for example: What do players try to do with the opponent's counters
in  backgammon?,  What  is  the size of the board used in backgammon?, How
many  counters  does  a  player have in backgammon?, etc. If you know what
backgammon  is,  and you just want to make sure that you do not forget the
name, you might just ask What is the name of the game I played with Robert
in  summer  1993?. However, if you are just a learner of languages, it may
appear  sufficient  to  learn  that backgammon is a kind of board game. In
Advanced  English, you will find the following item: 
Question: backgammon,
Answer: kind of game.
@ENDNODE



@NODE toolq&a "Questions concerning SuperMemo Toolkit"

Q: My computer was hit by a virus.  SuperMemo reports integrity errors and
I cannot work. What should I do?

A: Use  Miscellaneous:  Rescue  on the database.  Remember to back up your
database beforehand.


Q: I neglected my repetitions for too long. I want to start again with the
same database. What should I do?

A: Choose  Reset  option from menu on your database and start the learning
process from scratch (remember to set the correct date in your computer).


Q: I have created two databases and would rather use one.  How can I merge
databases?

A: Export  both  of them using Arexx script Print_DB.sm to text file. Join
them  (using editor or AmigaDOS features) and then import them using Arexx
script Make_DB.sm.


Q: I  have created my own question and answer files in ASCII. I would like
to convert them to SuperMemo databases. What is the easiest way?

A: Manually  or  programmatically,  convert  the  files to the text format
acceptable  by  Make_DB.sm  Arexx script (all question lines starting with
'Q: '  and all answer lines starting with 'A: '). Run Make_DB.sm (remember
to run Arexx server first)


Q: Can  SuperMemo  work  with other file formats, e.g., ASCII, DBase, CED,
MiAFile, Final Write etc.?

A: No.  However,  if  the  files contain data in the form of questions and
answers  (e.g.  word  pairs),  they  can  easily be converted to SuperMemo
format.  The  easiest way is to convert them to the TXT format accepted by
Make_DB.sm (see the chapter about SuperMemo Toolkit)


Q: I  create  a  database  and  use it together with my sister. How can we
share  files  so  that all correction introduced by me would automatically
appear in her databases?

A: Sharing  files  is  not  allowed between the databases of two different
users. You will not be able to edit both databases at the same time.


Q: How can I replace questions with answers in a word-pair database?

A: Choose Replace in the Edit window to replace a single item. In order to
replace whole database you should use an Arexx program.


Q: How can I print the content of a whole database?

A: Use  Make_DB.sm  Arexx script to convert a database to the text format,
and print the created text file.
@ENDNODE


@NODE theoryq&a "Theoretical questions"

Q: Why are intervals in SuperMemo so long?

A: They are as long as it takes to produce the desired proportion of items
to be forgotten at repetitions. If intervals are irritatingly long, reduce
the Lapses parameter in the Parameters dialog box.


Q: Why  are some items repeated in intervals that increase just by one day
between repetitions? I am certain that those intervals could be longer.

A: The intervals are as long as it takes to produce the desired proportion
of   items  to  be  forgotten  at  repetitions   (@{" forgetting index " link forgindex}).  If
repetitions  are  irritatingly  frequent,  increase  the  forgetting index
(Miscellaneous:Parameters:Lapses).


Q: Why  does  not  SuperMemo  mix  the   order  of  items   scheduled  for
repetitions?  I  have  introduced  some words in an alphabetical order and
they are asked in the same order at repetitions. This is not optimal.

A: True.  The major advantage of not reshuffling items is the fact that at
repetitions,  short  interval  items  are  asked  first.  The  learner has
a  general  feeling  of  how long intervals are assigned to items that are
currently  being  asked. This makes it possible to sharpen the accuracy of
grading   for  long-interval  items  whose  inaccurate  placement  in  the
repetition schedule has more severe consequences for the learning process.


Q: I  think that lower grades, e.g. 3, should produce shorter intervals in
comparison to higher grades, e.g. 5. It is not always so in SuperMemo.

A: In  SuperMemo, lower grades may produce longer intervals because of the
two following reasons:
- Grade  3  (Pass)  may   result  in  the  enhancement  of  the  so-called 
@{" spacing effect " link spaceeff},  which  may  be  less  visible for Grade 5 (Bright). The
spacing  effect  says  that  longer  intervals, and consequently a greater
recall  effort,  produce  more  stable  memory engrams. SuperMemo does not
arbitrarily  set  the function of optimal intervals. It computes intervals
which  are  most  likely  to result in the  @{" forgetting index " link forgindex}  defined in
Miscellaneous:Parameters:Lapses;   hence;  the   possibility   of   longer
intervals for lower grades.
- Irregularities in computing @{" optimal intervals " link optint} may also result from the
fact  that  some  entries of matrices can be computed more accurately than
others,  depending  on  the  number  of  repetition  cases recorded in the
process.   The  real-time  smoothing  of  them  is used to counteract this
problem.


Q: Why  can  I  not  see  the correlation between intervals and the grades
given in learning?

A: Your impression of no correlation between grades and intervals is quite
common  among  those  who begin their work with SuperMemo. It results from
the  fact  that  at  memorizing  new  items,  first intervals are randomly
dispersed  around  a  fixed  value.  This value comes from the model of an
average  learner, and can be modified only after the repetitions have shed
some  light  on if the value should be increased, decreased or kept at the
same  level.  Consequently,  it  will often happen that a lower grade will
produce  a longer interval and vice versa. At memorizing new items, grades
cannot  be used to estimate item difficulty because the program has no way
of  knowing  if  good  grades come from easiness of items or from the fact
that a given group of items has just been input to the database (inputting
items  is  a  form of repetition). You will start noticing the correlation
between grades and intervals in a week or two.


Q: Why  is the first interval after which the first repetition takes place
not equal in all cases?

A: It  is  randomly  modified  to speed up computing its optimum value, as
well  as  to  produce  smooth  distribution  of  the number of repetitions
scheduled over a period of a few days.


Q: Why  can I not see the effect of different grades during memorizing new
items, and during the @{" final drill " link drill}? Are grades used there, and how?

A:  At  memorizing  and  at  final  drill, the interpretation of grades is
limited  to  Pass  (4  or  more)  and  Fail  (less  than  4).  None of the
optimization   parameters  are  affected.  Here  are  the  reasons:  
- At  memorizing  new  items,  grades  cannot  be  used  to determine item
difficulty,  because  the  program  has  no way of knowing if a good grade
resulted from easiness of the item or from the fact that the user has just
input  the  given item to the database. Consequently, grades cannot affect
optimization,  and  are only used to detect items that should be scheduled
for final drill.
- Final  drill is not used for optimization either. This is because of the
fact  that  final  drill relies on short-term memory, and is substantially
more sensitive to inter-item interference as well as more dependent on the
number  of  other  items  separating  repetitions of the item in question.
Final  drill  is  used  solely  for  the  purpose  of fixing the forgotten
information  in  the  user's brain. Grades are used only to eliminate from
the final drill those items which score 4 or more.


Q: How  can  the  average interval (Interval in the main window) be longer
than the number of days I have spent on learning (Day in the main window)?

A: It  is  possible.  For  example,  imagine  that  you  have just started
learning  and  you  have memorized only one item. If its New Interval is 4
days you will have the following in the main window:
Day 1
Interval 4.0


Q: In  your materials I found a contradiction.  On one hand you claim that
once  learned  knowledge is constantly maintained in the learner's memory,
on  the  other  you  say  that after ceasing repetitions, I will gradually
forget what I have learnt. Which is true?

A: Both  facts are true.  The term 'maintained' is understood as 'actively
kept  in  memory  by  means of repetitions', not as 'remains in memory for
ever'.


Q: I  have  been  using your program for one week. In my estimation, I can
learn  no  more than 50-100% faster than without the program. Do you claim
that my estimation is conservative?

A: No.  The  power  of SuperMemo can only fully be observed after a longer
period  of  time.   This  comes  from  the   close-to-constant   knowledge
@{" acquisition rate " link acqrate}  in SuperMemo,  while  other  forms of learning produce
rapid  decrease  in  the  speed of learning in result of saturation of the
learning  schedule with randomly spaced repetitions. The estimation of the
50-fold   increase   in  the  speed  of  learning  concerns  the  lifelong
perspective. By using @{" mnemonic techniques " link mnemo}, you can easily beat SuperMemo
in  periods  of  up to one month.  In other words, SuperMemo will not work
for  those  who  want to cram a great deal of data before an exam.  On the
other  hand,  it  is  of  invaluable  help  for  those  who want to retain
indispensable facts and figures for months and years.


Q: Your  claim  that  SuperMemo allows me to learn at a speed that closely
approaches  the  maximum  speed with which memories can be formed does not
sound convincing. What evidence do you have to substantiate the claim?

A: For  a  given  collection  of  questions and answers SuperMemo computes
a  repetition  schedule that cannot be much improved by algorithmic means.
In  this  sense,  it gives you almost the best possible repetition timing.
Obviously,  there  is  a  great  number  of  elements that can improve the
learning process independently of SuperMemo. These are: (1) application of
@{" mnemonic techniques " link mnemo} (the same item may be memorized in a number of ways,
each  of  them  providing  different  stability  of  memory  traces),  (2)
repetition  procedure  and  environment,  (3) health and the status of the
learner's  mind,  (4)  pharmacological  factors,  etc.  Moreover, the same
knowledge may be represented in a different way (different order of items,
different  wording,  etc.) which may greatly affect the speed of learning.
As  far as SuperMemo optimization algorithms are concerned, their accuracy
cannot  be  greatly  improved  because  of  the  environmental  noise that 
@{" interferes " link interfer}  with  the  learning  process.  Each item may be more or less
consciously  repeated  in common life situations; the process being beyond
the control of SuperMemo.  Shortly speaking, if you are healthy, in a good
frame  of  mind,  you use mnemonics, and you use well-structured databases
under  the  supervision  of  SuperMemo, you may be quite sure that you are
getting  close  to  your maximum learning potential, and no natural method
can help you speed up learning by a substantial factor.


Q: (1)  I  want  to  spend my money on the MegaMemory program delivered on
cassette tapes. How would you convince me that I should rather spend money
on  buying  @{" SuperMemo " link sm}?  (2)  Is  SuperMemo  the  same  as  SuperLearning
developed  by  Dr  Georgi  Lozanov  from  Bulgaria?   (3) Which techniques
produce  a  greater  increase  in the speed of learning:  SuperMemo or the
mind maps proposed by Tony Buzan?

A: The  mnemonic  techniques (Tony Buzan, MegaMemory, etc.), SuperLearning
(Dr  Georgi  Lozanov) and SuperMemo are all complementary, and make up the
three  pillars  of  effective  learning.  All  of  them  have  to  do with
optimization:
- In  SuperLearning  the stress is on optimizing the cognitive environment
which produces the best effects on the learning process.
- In  @{" mnemonic techniques " link mnemo},  the representation of knowledge is optimized
in order to produce the most durable memory engrams.
- In SuperMemo,  the optimization concerns the @{" spacing of repetitions " link spacerep}.

To  be  a  successful learner, you have to apply mnemonic techniques while
using   SuperMemo  in  a  optimum  cognitive  environment.  The  important
advantage  of  SuperMemo  is that many capable learners develop quite good
techniques  as  far  as  mnemonics  is concerned. They can also reasonably
master their own physiology to subject it to the learning effort. However,
they  have  no way of optimizing the spacing of repetitions. Mostly due to
the fact that the amount and complexity of computation needed to determine
the  spacing require the use of a computer, and the technology proprietary
to  @{" SuperMemo World " link SMW}.  You are advised  to  follow  the teachings of Tony
Buzan,  Kevin  Trudeau  and  Georgi Lozanov; however, if you are a capable
learner,  you  can safely commit your foremost priority to learning how to
optimize your learning schedule. As for now, SuperMemo is the world's best
tool developed to assist you in this task.


Q: Tony  Buzan claims that the first review (second repetition) of an item
should take place in 24 hours. This is not so in SuperMemo. Why?

A: In  SuperMemo,  the  length  of the first interval is computed from the
forgetting  curve  plotted  in the course of repetitions to make sure that
a  defined  proportion  of  items  is  remembered;  usually  80-97%  (this
proportion is programmed by means of setting the @{" forgetting index " link forgindex} in the
option  Lapses).   Depending  on  the  forgetting index, the length of the
first interval may range from 1 up to 20 days, and is not set arbitrarily.
It  is  computed  from  the  record  of  repetitions and determined by the
requested forgetting index.  (requested forgetting index is the proportion
of items that are not remembered at repetitions)


Q: Tony Buzan claims that 75% of information is lost if not reviewed in 24
hours.  Does  it  not  defeat the validity of SuperMemo in which the first
interval is often longer than a week?

A: No.  In  the  context of self-paced drop-out learning technique used by
SuperMemo,  Buzan's  claim  is  certainly  invalid.  In  SuperMemo, if the
learner  chooses  the  retention  of  95%,  the typical value of the first
interval  falls  in  the  range  2-6 days depending on the learner and the
difficulty  of  the learned material. For retention 25%, the same interval
might be as long as one month, though it cannot be verified experimentally
with  SuperMemo  which  limits the range of the forgetting index to 3-20%,
and consequently the range of the overall retention to 85-99%.


Q: How do you respond to the accusation that the whole SuperMemo theory is
contradicted by the claim stated in the MegaMemory program of the American
Memory  Institute,  which says that forming indelible memories is possible
if suitable representation of the learned knowledge is used?

A: AMI  is a commercial,  not scientific institution. The claim that their
program  produces indelible memories can only be understood as part of the
marketing  strategy  used  to  promote  their  otherwise  very interesting
program.  The  concept of permastore has been proposed in a limited number
of publications in the field of psychology; however, the data collected in
the   research  on  molecular  aspects  of  memory  clearly  refutes  such
a  possibility.  In  SuperMemo, items whose optimal intervals reach beyond
the  biologically  determined  lifespan  can  be  considered  part  of the
permanent  memory store. The easiest way to disprove the AMI's claim is to
use  their  program to memorize a large body of intractable knowledge with
and  without  help  of  SuperMemo  (e.g. 1000 phone numbers would do). The
knowledge  retention after a 6-month-long period will stand at 85-98% with
SuperMemo  (depending  on  the  forgetting  index),  and  5-15% without it
(depending on individual capabilities)!


Q: How  can  you claim superiority of SuperMemo by comparing its retention
levels  with  those  obtained  in  the  MegaMemory  program? After all, in
MegaMemory  you  do  not  have  to spend time on repetitions! (compare the
previous question)

A: The  comparison  was  not supposed to show superiority of SuperMemo, it
was  only  intended  to  falsify  the  claim of the existence of indelible
memories. Mnemonic techniques and SuperMemo are complementary.


Q: Do  you  not think that the  @{" minimum information principle " link mininfo}  stands in
conflict  with  the  ages  old  rule  that the learned knowledge should be
highly associative in nature?

A: No.  The  minimum  information principle concerns the representation of
knowledge  in  SuperMemo  databases,  not  in  the  learner's  memory. The
principle does not prevent great advantages coming from proper structuring
of  the  learned  material.  In  the optimum situation, the learner should
first  construct  a  cohesive model of the learned subject, and only then,
apply  SuperMemo  to  make sure that the learned knowledge is sustained in
memory  as  a whole. The knowledge may be highly associative, but strictly
targeted  neural stimulation, achieved by means of granular representation
of  knowledge  in  SuperMemo, is necessary to effectively induce molecular
processes responsible for memory formation.


Q: On  what  basis  do  you ground your claim that SuperMemo increases the
speed of learning from 10-50 times?

A: For @{" knowledge retention " link knolret} of 95%, it can be computed that the number of
repetitions  in  an average learning lifetime (i.e.  about 60 years) is 50
times   greater  for  equally  spaced  repetitions  than  for  progressive
repetitions  (as  used  in  SuperMemo).   For  repetitions with no regular
spacing  scheme,  this  number  may  even  be  greater  (e.g.  traditional
read-and-review  textbook  learning).   Moreover, the greater the required
knowledge   retention,   the   greater   the  increase  in  the  knowledge
@{" acquisition  rate " link acqrate}   (classical  forms  of  learning  almost  never reach
 knowledge  retention  above  10%  in  periods  longer  than a year!).  In
practise,  users  of  SuperMemo  claim  that  it  increases their speed of
learning from 50% to 2000%.  These values are, however, highly subjective,
as  they  do  not  account  for the so-called intractable items, which are
practically  unmemorizable  without  SuperMemo.  In other words, SuperMemo
learners  tend  to  underestimate  the  fact that they can reach knowledge
retention  from  90  to  99%,  which would hardly be possible by using any
other method.


Q: How  can  you assume  that traditional learning involves equally spaced
repetitions? What length of intervals do you use to compare equally-spaced
and progressive schedules? (compare the previous question)

A: The  comparison  did  not  imply  that traditional learning is based on
equally   spaced  repetitions.  The  term  traditional  learning  is  used
throughout  this  book  to  denote  learning  with  no  regular pattern of
repetition   timing  (e.g.  2-4  repetitions  in  a  school  year  and  no
repetitions  later on). As the level of knowledge retention decreases here
gradually  from  95-100% to 0-5%, there is no comparable retention figure.
In  other  words,  traditional  learning  cannot compete with SuperMemo in
retention  categories  over  60%,  because  this retention is not possible
without  a  system  for  @{" repetition spacing " link repspace}.  Therefore,  equally-spaced
learning  was used as a substitute, in which a permanent retention of over
90%  is feasible and comparable with SuperMemo. The length of the interval
in  an  equally-spaced  schedule  is  determined by the level of knowledge
retention used in the comparison. Obviously, this will be exactly the same
value  as  the length of the first interval used by SuperMemo for the same
level  of knowledge retention (e.g. 2-20 days for retention 95%, depending
on the difficulty of the learning material).


Q: How  can  you  claim that retention of over 10% is hardly achievable by
other means than scheduling repetitions? Do you mean then that as a highly
skilled expert I know only 10% of what I have learned in my field?

A: A greatly talented reader, fluent in mnemonic techniques, might be able
to  recall  up  to  100%  of  a recently read book. However, this level of
knowledge  retention  cannot  be  maintained without repetition for longer
than  1-5  days. The 10% figure concerns the periods on the order of years
and  decades.  As  a  highly skilled expert you certainly remember 100% of
what  you have learned, but rather not much more than 10% of what you have
read  and  wanted to learn. Please recall hundreds of textbooks and dozens
of  courses  you  have taken before getting your present expert knowledge.
Pick  one of the books, open it at random and check how much you remember.
If  you could write your expert knowledge in the form SuperMemo items, you
would be surprised to see that it contains only 5-30 thousand items, which
you  could  have  memorized  in  just  a year. The books you have read and
courses   you   have   passed   must   have  contained  an  equivalent  of 
500,000-10,000,000 items.


Q: When  an  infant  burns  its  fingers,  it  will  not easily forget the
experience. How does it relate to your claim that nothing learned once can
be remembered for ever without repetition?

A: Some  low-level  memories  may differ in nature from memories typically
involved  in  high-level  learning.  This  results  from  the existence of
specialized  nervous  circuitry involved in storing inborn memories, which
may combine with newly acquired experience. This way, a number of reflexes
does  not  have  to  be  ever learned, and remains imprinted in memory for
lifetime.  However,  in  the  above case, one should not overlook the fact
that repetition of an unpleasant experience such as burning one's fingers,
does  not  have  to  be based on repeating the experience itself. The mere
fact  of  visual  contact  with flames, may invoke unpleasant memories and
serve as a @{" repetition " link rep}.  This way, each subsequent contact with fire, hot
plate,  etc.  will effectively function as a repetition, without a need to
experience the pain.


Q: Can SuperMemo be used to forget things?

A: Forgetting  is  a  molecular  process  that cannot easily be induced by
natural  methods.  The  more  so, there are no sensitive methods to induce
selective  forgetting,  though lesion to some parts of the cerebral cortex
may  produce  roughly  localized amnesia. However, there is a component of
forgetting  that  may be influenced.  This  component  is  @{" interference " link interfer}.
Whenever  we  learn  new  things,  they  always  interfere with previously
learned  material.  The  interference  may  enhance  some  memories  while
obliterating  others.  This  fact  can  be  used  to  employ  SuperMemo in
forgetting,  by formulating and memorizing a large number of contradictory
items  that  strongly  interfere  with  remembered  facts  that  are to be
forgotten.  However,  you  should  not  expect  the  effectiveness of such
a procedure to be anything but poor.


Q: Can I use SuperMemo to improve intelligence?

A: Yes.   Let  us  define   intelligence  as  the  capability  to  process
information.  Your  brain is like a computer: the better software it runs,
the  better  it performs. You can identify the elements of knowledge that,
for  example,  will  make  you perform better in intelligence tests. Those
elements,  if representable in audiovisual or textual form, can be used to
learn, and consequently, improve your intelligence.


Q: Soon  computers  will surpass human beings in their intelligence. Is it
not  better  to  invest  in  artificial intelligence rather than to try to
force  the  forgetful  memory to accomplish things with ever-disappointing
performance?

A: Without  disputing  the time table for the soon it is worth noting that
the  soon  may  become  sooner  if we intelligently use human intellectual
resources   which   are  indispensable  for  the  progress  in  artificial
intelligence.
@ENDNODE



@NODE SMW "About SuperMemo World"

The  first  SuperMemo  algorithm  based  on  optimizing  the scheduling of
repetitions  was  formulated in 1985. The first computer implementation of
SuperMemo  saw  the light in December 1987. In July 1991, a group of young
scientists  and  businessmen  from PoznaÔ, Poland, including the author of
the SuperMemo method, upon recognizing the immense commercial potential of
SuperMemo,  formed  a  company, SuperMemo World, whose only purpose was to
make SuperMemo a world-wide popular method of speed-learning. As expected,
SuperMemo  appeared  to  quickly  gain  popularity and recognition. It was
awarded  in many software competitions in Poland and abroad, and it became
one of the most popular software products in Poland.

